{ @@HeaderStart@@Introduction@@HeaderEnd@@  Welcome to this course on opening fundamentals!  I'm SmithyQ, and my goal is to teach you basic opening knowledge and principles.  This will give you a solid foundation for not just the opening, but for your entire chess development.  It's much easier to win games when you started on the right foot.  When you finish this course, you will be able to:  - play virtually any opening position confidently;  - avoid common opening mistakes;  - maximize your time; and,  - take advantage of your opponent's errors.  If anything is unclear or you would like more explanation on a given topic, let me know and I'll see what I can do.  Thank you for trusting me in this endeavour, and best of luck on your continued chess journey!  -- Jonathan 'SmithyQ' Pettit  April 2019 }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Course Layout"]
[Result "*"]

{ This course has been divided into three core sections, plus some bonus appendices.  First, there is the general Strategic section.  This details the overall STRATEGY of the opening.  This governs your thought-process; in other words, this will teach you how to think in the opening.  The basic opening principles are explained here, which will be the bedrock on which we build the rest of your knowledge.  This section is mostly lecture-based, though I've included MoveTrainer variations where possible.  Second, there is the Tactical section.  Many tricks and traps are common across all openings.  If you understand these common TACTICAL MOTIFS, you can take advantage of your opponent's errors  (and also avoid mistakes yourself)  .  The Strategic section tells you what to do in general, and this section will show you what to do in particular.  Third, there are the ANNOTATED GAMES.  These combine the above two sections and show proper opening play in action.  These games are annotated with words instead of endless variations, with particular focus on the ideas I teach in the first two sections.  You will see how following the opening principles from Section 1 lets you unleash the tactics found in Section 2.   (Note that, while attacking the King features heavily in these sections, the vast majority of this course focuses on the uncastled King.  Attacking the castled King is a huge area to cover, and it is more properly a middlegame concern, not the opening.  I will provide some general guidance here, but you will need specialized study from some other materials to learn this skill.)   I have concluded with two bonus appendices at the end.  These cover   i  practical advice I would tell young Smithy, and,   ii  suggestions on what to study next to complement what you learned in this course. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "The Opening Principles"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@The General Opening Principles@@HeaderEnd@@  There are only a few opening principles, and you can learn them all in a day.  These apply to virtually every position, and they form the bedrock of your game.  BEWARE: they look very simple, but the majority of beginner games violate these principles.  Do not confuse simplicity with being easy!  The fundamental idea of the opening is maximizing time.  A chess game starts with both sides having equal material and a symmetrical position.  The player that can make use of his or her pieces faster, in a more effective way, is generally the better player.  Time is everything in the opening, and all the opening principles are designed around maximizing time.  I will list them generally here, and the following sections will describe them with specific examples.   @@StartBlockQuote@@1. Develop Your Pieces@@EndBlockQuote@@This is really the whole point.  At the start of the game, your pieces do nothing.  Developing them lets them start attacking and defending and everything else.  You want ALL your pieces into the game as soon as possible.  This leads to a number of specific guidelines.  RULE 1: Move each piece once.  Do NOT move the same piece twice.  If you move your Knight three times and your opponent moves three pieces once, he has half his army out while you have one.  Every turn you spend moving a piece again, that's a turn you aren't developing.  Strive to finish development before moving those pieces again.  RULE 2: Focus on pieces.  Avoid unnecessary pawn moves.  You must move some pawns, of course, but only move pawns that help your development.  The goal is to develop your pieces, not your pawns.  In particular, moves like a3 and a6 are often the thief of time.  If you have a choice, favour pieces over pawns.  RULE 3: Place your pieces on 'good' squares in one move.  Do NOT hinder your own development.  In other words, don't get in your own way.  If you play 1. e4, this lets your Queen and Bishop move; if you then play 2. Ne2, the Knight blocks both of them, and the Knight will need to move again to let them free, wasting time.  This is best understood with examples, which I'll elaborate in the video and the following sections.  RULE 4: Develop minor pieces first; avoid bringing Rooks and Queens out early.  As a very general rule, the weaker a piece, the sooner it should be developed.  If you develop a Knight and your opponent attacks it with her Queen, who cares?  She won't take it.  Conversely, if you develop your Queen and she attacks it with a Knight, you care a lot.  You MUST move your Queen again, and that's violating the earlier rules.  In short, Knights and Bishops before Queens and Rooks.  And if your opponent brings her Queen out early, you can attack her to make her lose time.   @@StartBlockQuote@@2. Castle Early@@EndBlockQuote@@Checkmate ends the game.  If your King is weak, your whole game is weak.  I will show you many examples of one side self-destructing because they did not castle.  Now for the general guidelines:  RULE 5: Castle.  Just do it.  RULE 6: If possible, stop your opponent from castling.  If your opponent can't castle, that can be a decisive advantage by itself.  Look for ways to keep your opponent's King in the center.   @@StartBlockQuote@@3. Control the Center@@EndBlockQuote@@Of the three general principles, this one is understood the least.  In short, he who controls the center controls the game.  A Knight on  e5  can reach any part of the board in one move, ready for either attack or defence.  A Knight on  g8  takes three moves to reach the Queenside, and at least two moves to reach the opponent's side of the board.  In other words, controlling the center lets you go anywhere quickly, and your opponent will be slow to respond.  RULE 7: Have your pieces aim at the center.  In a perfect world your pieces would be on the center squares, but that's usually not possible.  The next best thing is to have your pieces aim at the center squares.  The more pieces aiming there, the better.  A Knight on  f3  aims at both  d4  and  e5  , whereas a Knight on  h3  aims at nothing.  That's why Nf3 is a better move than Nh3.  RULE 8: Get at least one pawn in the center, preferably two: e4 and d4.  Strictly speaking this is not completely necessary, but it is excellent practical advice.  If White has pawns on  e4  and  d4  , then he denies many central squares to Black's pieces.  A mobile pawn center can be an excellent attacking weapon, as we'll see.  That's it.  Those are all the opening rules.  Simple, right?  If you follow these guidelines, you are almost guaranteed a good game.  If you have a hard time remembering all 8 in a game, just focus on the Big Three Principles: Develop, Castle, Center.  The rest will follow.  The next page summarizes these in a single page, which may be useful for review or even printing.  There is one more mini-lecture on how to think in the opening, and then we'll explore practical examples of these principles. }
