[Black "Openings - The Most Important Idea"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@Openings – The Most Important Idea@@HeaderEnd@@  I mentioned this in the previous section, and since it basically summarizes the whole course in one sentence, I will write it again, in all caps:   @@StartBlockQuote@@TIME IS THE MOST IMPORTANT THING IN THE OPENING!!!@@EndBlockQuote@@By definition, this means everything else is NOT the most important.  This means the opening is  NOT about winning material, and it is   NOT about getting a better pawn structure, and it is   NOT about trying to win with an early attack.    The MOST IMPORTANT THING is getting your pieces out.  That's it.  That should be your dominant thought.  “Am I maximizing my time?  Am I bringing my pieces out as fast as possible?”  Of course, winning material, having good pawn structure and attacking are all good things, but they are not the goal of the opening.  They are, at best, a secondary goal.  Your main goal, your primary objective, is to maximize your time.    Develop.  Castle.  Control the center.  That's it.  This course will show numerous examples of attacking too early or trying to win material before finishing development.  They all lose.  The winners all have a lead in time.  All of them.  Time is everything.  @@HeaderStart@@Abstract: What is Time?@@HeaderEnd@@  In chess, time is expressed via how many moves it takes to do something; a single move is referred to as a tempo, with the plural being tempi.  Victory and defeat often hinge on a single tempo, and this is especially true in the opening.  Mastering time, or at least gaining a solid understanding of it, will significantly improve your results.  Every turn, we have a chance to move, and every time we move we change the position.  If we could move five times in a row, we'd have a five tempi advantage.  Of course, we can't move multiple times in a row, but if you watch a skilled player against a weaker one, it often seems like they do.  Please view the accompanying video to see a dynamic explanation of time and tempi.  Every opening principle revolves around maximizing time.  Time is literally everything.  Wasting time is throwing the game away.  If you get nothing else out of this course, remember this:   Time is everything. }
