[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Morphy's Opera Game"]
[Result "*"]

{ Morphy - Duke Karl / Count Isouard, Paris 1858  This classic Morphy game perfectly illustrates all the opening principles in action.  As this was played at the Opera, this is commonly referred to as the Opera Game. }
1. e4
{ This is a great opening move, because it both controls the center and lets two pieces get ready to develop. }
1... e5
{ Black responds in kind, also fighting for the center while preparing to develop his Queen and Bishop. }
2. Nf3
{ The Knight develops to its best square and threatens  e5  . This is called developing with tempo: White brings a piece out, and Black must react. }
2... d6
{ Protects the pawn, but now the Bishop is blocked in.  Do NOT hinder your own development. }
3. d4
{ White seizes the center and completes one of the opening goals: pawns to  e4  and  d4  if possible. }
3... Bg4
{ Developing a piece, which should be good, but here it is a tactical mistake. }
4. dxe5 { Black must either lose time or lose a pawn. } 4... Bxf3
{ If Black were to recapture  4...dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Nxe5  , he both loses a pawn and needs to lose more time to defend his loose pieces. }
5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4
{ White develops with tempo, threatening mate. White has two pieces out to Black's none, so he has a sizeable advantage already. }
6... Nf6
{ In fact, White's time advantage was so great that this standard move is a mistake! }
7. Qb3
{ Yes, Morphy moves his Queen again, but it hits both of Black's weaknesses. Black will need to waste more time trying to defend.  If you can make a move that forces your opponent to lose time, that's a net gain for you. }
7... Qe7
{ Black defends against  f7  and prepares to exchange Queens with Qb4. } 8. Nc3
{ Time is everything! The goal of the opening isn't to win pawns, it is to develop all your pieces.   8.Qxb7  Qb4+  9.Qxb4  Bxb4+  By exchanging Queens, Black has caught up in development at the cost of a pawn. Compared to the game, this is great. }
8... c6
{ This pawn move doesn't help with development, but how else do you stop Qxb7? }
9. Bg5
{ White has now finished developing all his minor pieces, and now he can castle in either direction. }
9... b5 { Oh no, another pawn move. } 10. Nxb5
{ Time is everything ! White gives up a piece to further increase his time advantage. }
10... cxb5 11. Bxb5+
{ White has two pawns for the piece, so he is barely even down material ... and look at his massive lead in development. }
11... Nbd7 12. O-O-O
{ It's move 12, and White has completed all the opening goals: he has developed every minor piece and castled. Here, castling even comes with tempo, as the Knight on  d7  is threatened. }
12... Rd8 13. Rxd7 { Another sacrifice ! Beautiful. } 13... Rxd7 14. Rd1
{ It's only move 14 and every White piece is active. Even better, every Black piece is tied down and can barely move. White is down material, but he is so far ahead in time that he has a winning position. }
14... Qe6
{ Black hopes to escape by exchanging Queens, but a final combination puts this to bed. }
15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Qb8+ Nxb8 17. Rd8#
{ This is a beautiful game, but let's look at it solely based on opening principles. Morphy developed with tempo every chance he could: Nf3, Bc4, even O-O-O came with tempo. Black made a number of unnecessary pawn moves, and White was able to sacrifice a piece for even more time. With all of White's army at maximum activity, Morphy found a tactical finish to cap off a fantastic game. If you just use opening principles, you can find most of White's moves. You might not play exactly like Morphy here, but if you follow the opening principles, your games will be powerful indeed.  For anyone who wants to memorize this game in full, there is a Chessable course for that: The Opera Game
  The following trainable examples look at these items in turn: developing with tempo, controlling the center and finishing games off tactically.  Let's have some fun! }
*

