[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Show how Morphy could have taken advantage in this possible variation. } 1.
Nf3
{ There are many good moves here, but Nf3 develops a piece, controls the center and forces Black to do something about his  e5  -pawn, so it's considered the best move. }
1... d6 2. d4
{ Simple development is possible, but this prepares to develop the  c1  -Bishop while also controlling the center.  It thus obeys two of the opening principles and is best. }
2... Bg4 3. dxe5 { This forces Black to either lose time or lose a pawn. } 3...
dxe5
{ In the game, Black instead played  3...Bxf3.  What happens if he were to recapture the pawn directly instead? }
4. Qxd8+ { Exchanging Queens breaks the pin. } 4... Kxd8 5. Nxe5
{ White is both a pawn up AND attacking both the Bishop and a potential fork on  f7  , forcing Black to waste further time.  White is up material, Black can't castle, White has no weaknesses: White is probably just winning.  'The Opera Game,' Morphy - Count Isouard and Duke Karl, Paris 1858. }
