{ How can Morphy further increase his time advantage? } 1. Qb3
{ Yes, this moves a piece twice, which is a loss if time ... but it forces Black to lose time himself defending against the dual threats.  Every move Black is defending is a move he isn't using to continue development.  Said another way, White spent one move on Qb3, but Black will need to spend at least two moves to defend and untangle, so White has effectively GAINED time. }
1... Qe7 2. Nc3
{ Development is more important than material!  2.Qxb7  Qb4+!  3.Qxb4  Bxb4+  and Black is temporarily ahead in development, plus with pressure on  e4.  White has won a pawn, but his advantage in time has slipped. Our focus, like Morphy's, should be time over material in the opening. }
2... c6 3. Bg5
{ White has developed all his minor pieces and has excellent attacking chances against Black's uncastled King.  'The Opera Game,' Morphy - Count Isouard and Duke Karl, Paris 1858. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Opera Game 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/pp2qppp/2p2n2/4p1B1/2B1P3/1QN5/PPP2PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... b5
{ Black is moving pawns instead of finishing development.  How should White react? }
2. Nxb5
{ A beautiful move.  As we'll learn, an advantage in time  (development)  works best in OPEN positions.  The fewer pawns, the more powerful pieces become.  By sacrificing the Knight, White gains two pawns and a powerful attack against an undeveloped enemy.    2.Be2  or something else would be passive, and Black would get a chance to catch up in time. }
2... cxb5 3. Bxb5+ Nbd7 4. O-O-O
{ Even castling comes with tempo, bringing another attacker against the pinned Knight on  d7  . Black can barely move, and Morphy has him right where he wants him.  'The Opera Game,' Morphy - Count Isouard and Duke Karl, Paris 1858. }
