[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 1 - Developing with Tempo"]
[Result "*"]

{ Steinitz - Bird, London 1866  A powerful idea is to develop with tempo; that is, to develop your pieces while also attacking your opponent, especially his Queen.  This is a prime example, where Black's Queen is developed early and is a potential target.  White will attempt to win time by attacking her. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Black's Queen is developed early, so that gives White a target to attack.  The goal is to develop our pieces while simultaneously hitting the Queen. }
6. Nf3
{ Nf3 is a developing move, which is great, and it also prepares Bg5 next.   If Black plays  6...h6  to stop  Bg5  , then he's using a turn not developing. Either way, we're gaining a lead in time. }
6... Nc6 { Black develops his Knight. } 7. Bg5
{ We develop our Bishop.  Now the Queen is forced to move. } 7... Qf5
{ The Queen is still a target here. } 8. Bd3
{ The Queen has to move again, and White's advantage in development grows. }
8... Qg4
{ White's pieces are surrounding Black's Queen, and she has very few squares. }
9. h3 Qxg2 { If  9...Qh5  ,  10.g4  also traps the Queen. } 10. Rh2
{ The Black Queen is trapped.  White took perfect advantage of Black's early Queen development, gaining time and even trapping her Majesty.    DO develop with tempo.  Do NOT bring your Queen out early, because she can be trapped. }
*

