[Black "Principles in Action 2 - Developing with Tempo"]
[Result "*"]

{ Another example of how to take advantage of early Queen moves. } 1. e4 d5 2.
exd5 Qxd5
{ Here, Black brought his Queen out early, which gives us a chance to attack it. If Black is careless, White can gain a big lead in development. }
3. Nc3 { White develops his Knight while attacking the Queen, a great move. }
3... Qe5+ { Black makes a check, but the Queen is still vulnerable here. } 4.
Be2
{ Playing Ne2 makes less sense here, as the Knight blocks both the Bishop and Queen from getting out. Do NOT hinder your own development. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ White now develops this Knight with tempo. Notice how White already has three minor pieces developed and is ready to castle, whereas Black keeps moving his Queen. }
5... Qe6 { Black tries to keep the pin, but even here the Queen is a target. }
6. O-O
{ White has most of his pieces developed and now he's castled, so his opening has been a success so far. }
6... g6
{ Black tries to develop his Bishop on the long diagonal, known as the fianchetto. Notice how Black's Queen is awkwardly placed, making it harder to develop his pieces: it blocks his own Bishop and stops the e-pawn as well. }
7. Re1
{ Other moves are fine, but this prepares a discovery against the Black Queen. When your opponent has a target, you should focus on that target with everything you've got. If you don't, then your advantage may slip. By playing Re1, Black must now waste more time, because if he continues with normal development... }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5+ { ... Black loses her Majesty. } 8... c6 9. Rxe6
{ You want to have a laser focus on developing with tempo. If your opponent has a target, such as bringing his Queen out early, then your primary focus should be trying to attack it and gain a superior lead in development.  DO develop as quickly as possible.   DON'T bring your Queen out early. }
