[SetUp "1"]

{ Show how White can develop with tempo against Black's careless play. } 1. Nc3
{ This is textbook developing with tempo, bringing a piece out while attacking the Queen. }
1... Qe5+ 2. Be2
{ 2.Qe2  trades Queens and rather lets Black off the hook.   2.Nge2  makes less sense, as the Knight blocks both the Bishop and Queen from getting out. Do NOT hinder your own development. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White now develops this Knight with tempo. Notice how White already has three minor pieces developed and is ready to castle, whereas Black keeps moving his Queen. }
3... Qe6 4. O-O
{ 6.Ng5 ?  attacks the Queen, but the Knight moves twice; this doesn't help White's development, so it is not a good idea. Remember, if a move does not help our development, it is a wasted one. }
4... g6 5. Re1
{ Because Black's Queen is still vulnerable, our focus should be harassing her every chance we get. }
5... Bg7 6. Bb5+ { With a discovered attack on the Queen. } 6... c6 7. Rxe6
{ You want to have a laser focus on developing with tempo. If your opponent has a target, such as bringing his Queen out early, then your primary focus should be trying to attack it and gain a superior lead in development.  DO develop as quickly as possible.  DON'T bring your Queen out early. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 3 - Developing with Tempo"]
[Result "*"]

{ Alekhine - Bruce, Plymouth 1938  Attacking the Queen is one way to develop with tempo.  It's also possible to attack loose pieces and/or threaten the King to gain time.  The 4th World Champion Alekhine shows us a master class here. }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ White recaptures his pawn and temporarily has a two-move lead in development. }
4... Bf5 { Black attacks the White Knight ... } 5. Ng3
{ White retreats, but in doing so attacks the undefended Bishop.  Black must react. }
5... Bg6 6. h4
{ This is a pawn move, but it is a good one: White threatens to trap the Bishop with h5, and Black must spend time to prevent this. }
6... h6 7. Ne5
{ White now threatens Nxg6, destroying Black's structure.  True, White is moving a piece for the second time, but Black is also forced to react.  White correctly calculated that he will gain more time than he will lose with this maneuver.  Let's watch. }
7... Bh7
{ Black retreats.  Notice how Black still only has one piece developed. } 8.
Qh5 { White threatens mate, and there's only one reasonable way to stop it. }
8... g6 { Black's only developed piece is now entombed. } 9. Bc4
{ White develops with tempo again, threatening mate ... again! } 9... e6
{ Black again prevents mate, but White has gained a large lead in development thanks to his threats. }
10. Qe2
{ On first glance, you might think White has broken the rules: he's made unnecessary pawn moves, he's moved his pieces twice, he's brought his Queen out early ... but White also has a four move lead in development.  Remember, TIME IS EVERYTHING.  If you can move your piece twice but gain a lead in time, do it!  That's always the ultimate goal.  White's lead in time is so large, he can finish the game instantly. }
10... Nf6 11. Nxf7 { White's lead in development now becomes decisive. } 11...
Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Kg7 13. Qf7#
{ In this game, White gained a large lead in development by first attacking the Bishop and then by attacking the King.  White won this game by constantly developing with tempo, and that led to a fancy finish.  DO develop with tempo.  DO combine threats with development if possible.  DO break the rules if it means gaining a net increase in time!  If moving a piece twice leads to a gain in time, do it.   (Fun fact: I have won with this exact series of moves three times!  Opening principles are powerful!) }
*

