[SetUp "1"]

{ Keep increasing White's lead in time. } 1. Qh5
{ This gains time by threatening mate and forcing Black to entomb his Bishop.   Other moves, like  1.d4  , are good, but they don't maximize White's time advantage.   The most common error here is  1.Qf3  , which simply allows Black to play  1...Nf6  , and White does not have the sacrifice ready as in the mainline. }
1... g6 2. Bc4
{ Developing with tempo, and again threatening mate on f7.   2.Qe2?!  brings the Queen all the way back just to block in his own Bishop. Do NOT hinder your own development. }
2... e6 { Taking the Queen leads to swift mate  9...gxh5  10.Bxf7# } 3. Qe2
{ Qe2 threatens devastation after Nxf7. Qf3 is also good.   3.Qg4  makes less sense because then Black's reply  3...Nf6  gains time. If we want to develop with tempo, we certainly don't want to allow our opponent to do the same. }
3... Nf6 4. Nxf7
{ Because White has such a large lead in time, tactical shots like this should be your first thought. Something like  4.O-O  lets Black untangle. }
4... Kxf7 5. Qxe6+ { Black's pawn cover has been eradicated. } 5... Kg7 6. Qf7#
{ From Alekhine - Bruce, Plymouth 1938 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 4 - Development Without Queens I"]
[Result "*"]

{ Duras - Jes, Pisek 1912  Many people think that, if there are no Queens, then a lead in development doesn't matter. While Queens certainly help, a lead in development can be decisive even when they have been exchanged. Let's look at a few examples. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit: White offers a pawn to take better control of the center and hopefully quick development. }
2... exf4 3. Nf3 d5
{ An excellent response by Black. He immediately returns the pawn to gain his share of the center and speed up his own development. }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ This, though, is risky. Black brings his Queen out early, where she can be attacked. Better is  4...Nf6 }
5. Nc3 { White immediately develops with tempo... } 5... Qh5
{ ... and Black goes to a funky square. } 6. d4 Bg4 7. Bxf4 Bxf3
{ Here's where I point out that Oldrich Duras, White, was one of the strongest players in the 19th century; Black was an amateur. Black is doing something that many amateurs do when facing a stronger opponent: trying to exchange Queens at all cost. Yes, he gets the Queens off the board ... }
8. Qxf3 Qxf3 9. gxf3
{ ... but look at this position. White is massively ahead in development, and he is threatening to immediately win the  c7  -pawn. Black perhaps thought he was safe, but a lead in development can be deadly even without Queens. }
9... Nc6
{ Black's position was so bad that this natural developing move nearly loses on the spot. }
10. Bxc7 Nxd4 11. O-O-O
{ White castles with tempo, offering the f-pawn. The center is completely open and Black's King is in real danger. Black tries to block the e-file with }
11... Ne6 { but now the lead in development is decisive. } 12. Bb5+ Ke7 13.
Nd5#
{ Development matters, even without Queens. Black could not parry White's threats with his sleeping army, and he ended up getting checkmated anyway.   DO develop with tempo.   Do NOT bring your Queen out early  (and do not think exchanging Queens automatically makes you safe) }
*

