[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 5 - Development without Queens II"]
[Result "*"]

{ Steiner - Stiassny, Brunn 1925   This is another example of pieces running over a sleeping army, even without Queens. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4
{ The Queen's Gambit. Similar to the King's Gambit, White offers a pawn to speed up his development and gain better control of the center. }
2... c5 { Black offers a pawn in turn ! Very strange. } 3. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black has made three moves, all with pawns. Uh oh. } 4. Nc3 cxd4
{ That's the fourth pawn move ! Black is moving nothing but pawns ! } 5. Qxd4
{ By contrast, White has three pieces out already. } 5... Qxd4
{ Seeing White's lead in development, Black exchanges Queens. This is the right idea, but he must stay vigilant. }
6. Nxd4 a6
{ This is not vigilant ! Another pawn move ! Black has done absolutely nothing in the opening, and now White looks to punish him. }
7. Nd5
{ This moves a piece twice, true, but it creates powerful threats. White is threatening either Nb6 or Nc7+, picking up material. If you can force your opponent to lose time dealing with your threats, then you are still winning time. }
7... Kd8
{ This is forced. You know things are bad when your only developed piece is your King. }
8. Bd2
{ A simple developing move, but one with venom: Ba5+ is threatened, taking advantage of the King's poor position. }
8... Nd7 { Black finally develops a piece ... and it's the losing move ! } 9.
Ba5+ { Now the White pieces become a swarm. } 9... b6 10. Nc6+ Ke8 11. Nc7#
{ Developing is so important. Notice that in the final position, Black is still up a pawn. Did that pawn help him ? Of course not. He was careless, making unnecessary pawn moves and falling so behind in development that he was helpless. Even without Queens, development is paramount.   DO develop with tempo.   Do NOT make unnecessary pawn moves. }
*

