[SetUp "1"]

{ Prove that White's lead in development matters, even without Queens. } 1. Nd5
{ Bringing the Knight to  d5  forces Black to defend against the  c7  and  b6  fork threats.  It doesn't develop a piece, but it forces Black to weaken his position, so it is a good move.  Also, Black is so far behind in development that White may look for ways to punish Black.  This is the best punishment.  e4 and Bf4 are also good, following the opening principles.  They do give Black a chance to untangle, though. }
1... Kd8 2. Bd2
{ There are many good moves, but when your opponent has a weak King, you should focus on how to take advantage of it somehow.  Bd2 threatens a nasty check on  a5  and is best. }
2... Nd7 3. Ba5+ b6 4. Nc6+
{ If you took the pawn on  b6  , hang your head in shame, you missed a mate in 2! }
4... Ke8 5. Nc7#
{ A lovely finish highlighting the power of development, even without Queens.  From Steiner - Stiassny, Brunn 1925. }
