[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 6 - Development without Queens III"]
[Result "*"]

{ Dodge - Houghteling, Chicago 1905  Proof that Black can win games by following opening principles as well, even without Queens ! This may be the prettiest final position I've ever seen. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 { Black offers a gambit to speed up his development. } 3. e3
{ White declines the gambit, but notice how this restricts his Bishop. Spoiler alert, that Bishop never moves, mostly because of that pawn ! }
3... exd4 4. Qxd4
{ White brings his Queen out early, which as we know makes it a target of attack. }
4... Nf6
{ Black needs to defend before playing Nc6.   4...Nc6 ?  5.Qxd5  and White wins the pawn }
5. Nc3 Nc6 { Black develops with tempo. } 6. Qd1 Bf5
{ After six moves, Black has three pieces out to White's one. White needs to be careful... }
7. f3
{ ... this is not careful ! There are about a billion things wrong with this move: it weakens the King, it's an unnecessary pawn move, White is further behind in development,  f3  cannot be used for a Knight, if the Knight goes to  e2  instead then the Bishop can't move, HOLY COW ! }
7... Nb4
{ As in the previous game, Black moves a piece twice, but he has such a large lead in time he can look to punish his opponent.  He is threatening a fork on  c2  , and White has a tough time defending it. }
8. Qa4+ Qd7
{ This move lets White off the hook somewhat: simply blocking the check with c6 makes Nc2+ unstoppable. After White's next mistake, though, this leads to a beautiful finish, so I guess I shouldn't complain too much.  That said, if you are ahead in development, you normally want to KEEP Queens on. A lead in development is always powerful, but it is much more powerful with Queens. }
9. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ Queens are off, but Black still has a lead in development and still threatens Nc2+. White now goes insane. }
10. e4
{ White must have miscalculated: this both loses a pawn and opens the game up while behind in development. True, it stops Nc2+, but it allows something far worse ! }
10... dxe4 11. fxe4 Nxe4
{ Black still has three pieces developed to White's one, and two of them are monster Knights. }
12. Rb1
{ White tries to side-step the Nc2+ fork by moving his Rook, but this nothing move allows Black to fully invade. }
12... Nc2+ 13. Kd1 Nf2+ 14. Ke2 Bc5 { Developing over winning more material ! }
15. Nf3 Bd3+ 16. Kd2 Be3#
{ The minor pieces form a rainbow of destruction for the White King. This game is fantastic just for the sheer aesthetics of this final position, but notice again an edge in development leading to victory even without Queens.   Time is everything. }
