[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 7 - Controlling the Center I"]
[Result "*"]

{ Greco - NN, 1620   So far, we've seen the power of development; this game will show us the power of controlling the center. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 { Both sides are developing normally. } 4. c3
{ This is a pawn move, but it prepares to play d4 and dominate the center. It's one of the best plans available for White. }
4... Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 { White's center is a thing of beauty. } 6... Bb6
{ This retreat lets White's center walk all over Black.   6...Bb4+  was absolutely necessary }
7. e5 { Boom. The pawns go marching, kicking Black away. } 7... Ng8 8. d5
{ Boom. } 8... Nce7 9. d6
{ Boom again ! The pawns have completely shattered Black's position, giving White a huge initiative. }
9... Nc6 10. Qd5
{ White, in fact, threatens mate, and there's not much Black can do ! } 10...
Nh6 { Black defends  f7  . } 11. Bxh6 { So White removes the defender. } 11...
Rf8 { 11...gxh6  12.Qxf7# } 12. Bxg7
{ Black's position is in shambles, and he resigns in just a few moves. } 12...
Nb4 13. Qd2 Rg8 14. Bf6
{ To top it off, he loses his Queen as well.   Controlling the center is extremely powerful. If you can get your central pawns to march forward, it often leads to a devastating initiative.   Also worth noting that, by move 6, Black actually had three pieces developed to White's two. However, he had no central control at all, and he was swept off the board not even 10 moves later. Development is important, but don't forget about the center ! We'll see a few more examples to hammer this home. }
*

