[Result "*"]

{ Albin - Shipley, New York 1894   A very similar example of the central crush, but compared to Greco - NN, both sides castle first. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O
{ In our previous game, Greco played c3 immediately here. Both options are of course fine. }
4... Nf6 5. c3
{ White is prepared to sacrifice his e-pawn in order to play a quick d4 and gain a lead in development. Time is everything ! }
5... O-O
{ Black rejects the pawn and castles. This ignores the center, though. } 6. d4
exd4
{ Taking the pawn gives White too much influence over the center. Better was   6...Bb6  7.dxe5  Nxe4  with chances for both sides. }
7. cxd4 Bb6
{ Just like Greco, White has a mobile pawn center, so he should push it ! } 8.
d5 Ne7 9. e5 Ne8 10. d6
{ Look familiar ? The same ideas come up again and again. If you master the principles, the right moves come naturally. }
10... cxd6 11. exd6 Ng6
{ Black's Bishop will be stuck for a very long time, whereas White can freely develop everything with ease. }
12. Bg5 { White develops with tempo, and the Black Queen is nearly trapped. }
12... Nf6 13. Nc3 h6
{ Black tries to push White back, but he is so far ahead in development that he can look for a tactical breakthrough. }
14. Qd3
{ White ignores the threat and develops his Queen. Notice that this is NOT developing the Queen too early: White has all of his minor pieces out, and Black has no way of attacking her Majesty. }
14... hxg5 15. Qxg6 { Because the pawn is pinned, White's Queen is immune ! }
15... Nh7 { Black tries desperately to untangle. } 16. Nd5
{ White just marches forward, and the threats are irresistible. } 16... fxg6
{ Black wins the Queen but loses his King. } 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. Nxg6#
{ White dominated the center and used his mobile pawns, and Black was powerless to resist.  DO develop with tempo.   DO control the center. }
