[Black "Principles in Action 9 - Controlling the Center III"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lee Passmoor vs. Leif E Warstad, 1999   One more example will show the power of the center, and that being up in material means little if your pieces can't do anything. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ So far, so good: both sides developing sensible. Then White goes insane. } 4.
Nxe5
{ This is called the Halloween Gambit. White is sacrificing an entire piece just so he can control the center ! It's probably not sound, but it's undoubtedly dangerous. }
4... Nxe5 5. d4 { We see White's idea clearly: his pawns are free to march. }
5... Nc6
{ This gives White precisely what he wants.   5...Ng6  is more common. } 6. d5
{ Pawns go marching ! } 6... Ne5 7. f4 { The f-pawn joins the fun. } 7... Ng6
8. e5 Ng8 9. d6 { The same ideas again and again ! } 9... cxd6 10. exd6 Qf6
{ Black prepares to attack . If that pawn falls, then Black will simply be a piece up. }
11. Nb5 { White defends his pawn and threatens Nc7+. } 11... Kd8
{ This isn't the main error, but it's very important. Why did Black play this ? Because he was worried about Nc7+ ... but he's already up a piece ! He doesn't need to worry about 'losing' material because he's already up material. Time is everything !   11...Nh6  is simple, finishing development. Who cares if White checks on  c7  ?  12.Nc7+?!  Kd8  13.Nxa8  Bxd6  The Knight in the corner is trapped and Black is nearly fully developed. White no longer has a central advantage and is in big trouble. If Black weren't so concerned about material, if he thought about time, he would be winning  ! Instead... }
12. Be3
{ White develops, and the  a7  -pawn is attacked. Should Black be concerned with that pawn ? If you said no, time is everything and Black should keep developing, give yourself a gold star. If you said yes, the measly little pawn on the side of the board is important and Black should spend his valuable time to defend it, well ... }
12... a6
{ Black was focused on material, not time. That's the only explanation for his last two moves. Now we get an amusing finish. }
13. Bb6+ Ke8 14. Nc7+
{ Now Nc7+ not only picks up material, but it sets up an unstoppable windmill. }
14... Kd8 15. Nxa8+ Ke8 16. Nc7+
{ Black resigned here, as Nd5+ discovered check will win his Queen. In this game, White played a likely unsound sacrifice, but it gave him control of the center. That control put Black under pressure, and he then cracked. I'm not saying you should be sacrificing pieces for central pawns every chance you get, but I am saying that the center is extremely powerful, even if down material. And if you aren't down material AND have complete control of the center, you are likely winning.  Most amateurs don't fully understand the power of the center. Don't be most amateurs. Respect the center.   DO control the center.   Do NOT play strange moves trying to not lose material when you are already up a whole bunch of material and you could just finish development !!!  (or, you know, Time is everything) }
*

