[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 9.1 - Controlling the Center III"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4n3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is down a piece.  How can he play to justify this? } 1. d4
{ White has just sacrificed a piece, so we need decisive action.  Claim the center and push your pawns! }
1... Nc6 2. d5
{ If you have a pawn center, push it!   Unlike the other examples concerning the center, move order is important here.  6.e5?!  is less precise, because after  6...Ng8  White cannot play  7.d5?  anymore because of  7...Nxe5. }
2... Ne5 3. f4 { Even the f-pawn gets in the action. } 3... Ng6 4. e5
{ In case it isn't obvious, this entire drill is just pushing pawns.   You have to push the right ones, though.  8.f5?  Ne5  just gives Black a great position for his Knight, thank you very much. }
4... Ng8 5. d6
{ If we don't play d6 here, Black will either play it himself and contest our center, or he will play Bb4 and get his Bishop developed.  Playing d6 stops these ideas and keeps the pressure on. }
5... cxd6 6. exd6
{ White is not winning here, of course, because he started down a piece, but his central dominance gives him a fighting chance.  From Lee Passmoor vs. Leif E Warstad, 1999. }
