[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action 10 - Don't Hinder Your Development"]
[Result "*"]

{ We've discussed the importance of development, so now let's turn to what makes development effective.  By the end of the opening, we want to have all our pieces developed and active.  This means any move that restricts our activity, or that hinders our ability to develop, should be avoided.  Here are some examples of things to avoid. }
1. e4
{ After 1.e4, for instance, both White Queen and Bishop can develop.  That's great, and it's not a move to avoid! }
1... e5 2. Ne2
{ If we play Ne2, though, then those pieces cannot move again.  We either need to make more pawn moves to get them out, which is a waste of time, or move the Knight again, which is also a waste of time.  This is an example of hindering development. }
2... Bd6
{ Black's Bd6 here is another example.  The Bishop doesn't do much here, as it only stares at its own pawns, and it also hinders Black's d-pawn from advancing and letting his other Bishop in the game.  Black will likely need to move this Bishop again, both to aid development and also just to put it on a more open diagonal.    As a general rule, Bishops don't like being directly in front of central pawns. Compare this with  2...Bc5  , where the Bishop is on a great diagonal and the d-pawn can easily move. }
3. g3 Be7 4. Bg2
{ White has developed his Bishop, yea!  But it stares right at its pawn, boo!  The Bishop could have gone to  c4  on move 2, where it had a beautiful diagonal; instead, White has spent three moves developing this Bishop  (e4, g3, Bg2)  to a square it barely does anything. }
4... d6
{ Black now prepares to develop his light-square Bishop, which is great ... but now his other Bishop is entombed.    I won't belabour this point with any more silly examples.  The idea is quite clear: if you can put your pieces on good squares in one move, do it.  Development means more than just moving our pieces.  It means putting them on good squares and making them more active.  All the examples here are making the pieces less active  (or, at best, neutral)  .  Making moves that don't improve your position is by definition a waste of time. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Time is Everything "]
[Result "*"]

{ I want to hammer this home: time is everything.  This means, very often, time is MORE IMPORTANT than material, or at the very least just as important.  Observe the following game snippet, where White  (a beginner)  plays for material and Black  (that's me!)  for time. }
1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ This is a poor move, bringing the Queen out early. It does have a threat of taking the e5-pawn, though. Black can defend the pawn, and of course  2...Nc6  is a perfectly reasonable response, but there is another option. }
2... Nf6
{ An interesting idea!  Black is giving up his e-pawn, but he is gaining a lead in development.  Watch. }
3. Qxe5+ Be7 4. d4
{ Things look great for White.  He has a big center, a centralized Queen and an extra pawn... but it's Black to move, and he's about to gain a big lead in time. }
4... Nc6
{ Black now has three pieces developed, and White's Queen needs to move again.  In fact, no matter where the Queen moves, Black will win back a pawn. }
5. Qg3 { White attacks  g7  . } 5... Nxe4
{ Black wins back a pawn and attacks the Queen again.  The Knight is now the best piece on the board. }
6. Qxg7 { White wins a pawn... } 6... Bf6
{ ... but Black attacks it again, and now the Bishop is the second best piece on the board. }
7. Qh6
{ White has moved his Queen five times in the first seven moves, and she's ended up on a poor square on the side of the board. }
7... Nxd4
{ Black, by contrast, has three excellent pieces completely dominating the board.  Black has a massive lead in development, which is a lead in TIME.  He is threatening  c2  with a fork, and he can easily develop the rest of his pieces with d5, Qe7, Bf5 and 0-0-0.  White is hanging on for dear life, and he isn't even up material!  White tried to win material, whereas Black played to maximize his time.  Black isn't just better, he is MUCH better.  If you focus on maximizing your time on every move, you will get positions like Black; if you don't, you are in danger of being White.  Time is everything. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section I - General Principles"]
[Black "Principles in Action - General Conclusion"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@HeaderStart@@General Conclusions@@HeaderEnd@@  In all the above examples, and in all the examples that will follow, pay attention to these factors:  Notice how often the winning side had BETTER PIECES.  A lead in time almost always equals better pieces.  Notice how many NICE TACTICS appeared, almost out of nowhere.  A lead in time often gives you amazing tactical possibilities, and we'll see many more in the sections that follow.  Notice how KING SAFETY doomed the losing side.  In almost every instance, the losing side failed to castle, which allowed tactics and other misfortune.  We will explore these ideas in greater detail in the Tactical section next.  For now, notice how all three factors come about from an advantage in TIME.  Time is everything!  I've hoped I convinced you of this so far, and there'll be many more examples to come.  One last note: as Bobby Fischer said, “Tactics flow from a superior position.”  If you follow the opening principles, you will get a good position, and then you can look for tactics.  The next section will tell you exactly what to look for. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "A Theory of Time"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ @@HeaderStart@@A Theory of Time@@HeaderEnd@@  The first section, on general principles, was concerned with gaining time.  Now we'll learn exactly how to use it.  Time is the most elusive of the main positional factors.  If you are up a Queen, for instance, then you are up material, and unless you blunder it back, you'll always be up in material.  An advantage in time, though, can be fleeting.  If you do not act quickly, your opponent may catch up in development and your advantage disappears.  The first step, of course, is to get that lead in development by following the general principle.  There are three steps you should then follow:  1. Keep developing with tempo and creating threats.  Your opponent can't finish development if he is always stuck defending, and this can increase your advantage even more.  2. Advance pawns and open lines.  The more pawns are exchanged, the more powerful a lead in development becomes.  2.1 Consider sacrifices, as they can open lines as well.  3. Constantly look for a way to 'cash-in'.  Most combinations start because of an advantage in development.  This third point requires calculation and hard work, but I will give you a shortcut.  In this section, I will show you the most common tactical motifs in the opening.  Once you learn these and drill them over and over, you will see these same ideas in your own games quickly and automatically.  Let me tell you, that's a pretty cool feeling.  Remember, time is everything.  Master this and your game will transform. }
*

