{ Smithy - 'Knightmare,' Internet, 2002  (fragment)    This is based on an early game I played. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3
{ 3.e4  is the aggressive way to play, immediately seizing the center. There is nothing wrong with developing, of course. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 { Simple development, preparing to win back the pawn. } 4... Bg4
{ Whenever Black plays this in this type of structure, he needs to beware of potential tactics. }
5. Bxc4 a6
{ This is from one of my early games.  I see the weakness on  f7  and pounce: }
6. Ne5
{ 6.Bxf7+  This is also thematic and good.  Kxf7  7.Ne5+  Ke8  8.Nxg4  Nxg4  9.Qxg4  The advantage of Ne5 first is that it threatens mate. }
6... Bh5
{ 6...Bxd1  7.Bxf7#   6...Be6  This is the only move to stay in the game, though  7.Bxe6  fxe6  is extremely ugly.  Black uses his Bishop to defend  f7  , but this has a fatal flaw. }
7. Qxh5
{ In the game, I missed this killer move, instead playing  7.Qb3  , which is also good ... but I ended up losing the game in the end! So if you found  Qxh5  , you are doing better than young Smithy!  All of White's forces are attacking  f7  , and the game is decided. }
7... Nxh5 8. Bxf7#
{ It's been nearly 20 years, but I'm still upset I missed this.  It would have been my first ever  (intentional!)  Queen sac.  We will look at several more simple Bxf7+ sacrifices, and then build up to some more complex material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
