{ Rudolf Johannes Loman vs. Emanuel Lasker, Amsterdam 1889  The opening was a common one in master levels, known as the Ruy Lopez. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6
{ So far, both sides are developing and castling like good boys. } 5. O-O d6
{ This is a solid way of playing: Black 100% protects  e5  against any tactics, but it blocks his Bishop in. }
6. Nc3 b5 7. Bb3 Bg4 { Again, both sides with natural development. } 8. h3 Bh5
9. d3 Nd4
{ Black puts extra pressure on  f3  , as well as getting the c-pawn ready to go.  This is moving a piece twice before finishing development, though. }
10. Kh2 g5
{ Lasker was World Champion and a ridiculously strong player for a very long time.  He's a giant of chess history ... but this is a poor move.  The opening isn't about attacking! }
11. g4 Nxg4+
{ This was Black's idea, as after the sacrifice he has a very strong pin... or so he thinks. }
12. hxg4 Bxg4 { Let this one serve as a warning. } 13. Bxf7+
{ White sees the loose Bishop on  g4  and prepares the standard Bxf7+ sacrifice. }
13... Kxf7 14. Nxg5+ Qxg5
{ This temporary Queen sac refutes White's idea. This is a common occurrence, so always DOUBLE CHECK YOUR TACTICS !  White clearly envisioned something like   14...Ke8  15.Qxg4  when he picks up the Bishop. }
15. Bxg5 Bxd1 { If White recaptures on  d1  , then } 16. Raxd1
{ 16.f4  In the game, White tried to gain counterplay against Black's King, but the future World Champion had no problems.  Bg4  17.fxe5+  Kg6  18.Bf6  Bg7  19.Rf4  h5  20.Raf1  Raf8  21.Nd5  dxe5  22.R4f2  Bxf6  and here White resigned. }
16... Nf3+ 17. Kh1 Nxg5
{ Black ends up with an extra Bishop and a winning position. Just because you see a common tactic doesn't mean it works. ALWAYS DOUBLE CHECK YOUR TACTICS ! }
*

