[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Weakness on f7 7"]
[Result "*"]

{ De Legal - Saint Brie, Paris 1750 } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 Bg4 4. Nc3 g6
{ We now come to one of the most beautiful of the Bxf7 motifs, the Legal Mate. We see the standard  Bg4  pin, and it's undefended, but the immediate Bxf7 does not work. That's where the spectacular ... }
5. Nxe5 { ... comes in, giving up the Queen ! } 5... Bxd1
{ 5...dxe5  6.Qxg4  is relatively best, where Black 'only' loses a pawn with a terrible position. }
6. Bxf7+ Ke7 7. Nd5#
{ White's pieces coordinate beautifully to finish off the Black King. I keep saying it, but time is everything. Here, Black is up a full Queen, but White is the one with three active pieces, and those pieces give mate. This pattern appears again and again  (and it's so pretty !)  , so we'll see several more examples. }
