{ Oudheusden - De Vries, Amsterdam 1934 } 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 Bc5 4. Nf3
d6 5. f5 Nf6 6. h3 d5 7. Nxe5 Nxe4 8. Nf3
{ It's not only White that has all the fun. Black can do it as well. Here, the immediate Bf2+ is fine, but }
8... Qh4+
{ There is nothing wrong with  8...Bf2+  9.Ke2  , which is, of course, excellent for Black, but the immediate Legal idea of  Nd4+ ?  10.Nxd4  doesn't work. If Black could get rid of the Knight on  f3  (, then this combination would work. That's why)  8...Qh4+  (! is so brilliant.) }
9. Nxh4
{ With  d4  free, we now have a standard Legal pattern, but with an extra twist. }
9... Bf2+ 10. Ke2 Nd4+ 11. Kd3 Nc5#
{ When you have a big lead in development against an uncastled King, Legal's Mate is always worth looking for. }
