{ Hamlisch - NN, Vienna 1902 } 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nd7
{ White is a master; Black is an amateur.  White is controlling the center; Black is ... not.  If Black knows what he is doing, he might be okay. }
3. Bc4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7
{ Black has given White the center on a platter, and White can cash in immediately. }
5. Bxf7+ { Bam.  This is how fast the game can turn. } 5... Kxf7 6. Ng5+
{ Black has three possibilities. All of them lose. } 6... Kf6
{ 6...Ke8  7.Ne6  and the Queen is trapped.   6...Kf8  7.Ne6+  and the Queen is forked. }
7. Qf3#
{ The weakness on  f7  decided this game by move 7. Ignore it at your peril. Conversely, it's never too early to look for Bxf7 ideas.  Edit: Fun fact.  This very game appeared at Lichess, where a 2300 bullet player made this exact blunder, and his 2500 opponent punished him in 2 seconds.  If you learn these common tactics, maybe you can do the same!  GM Kastorcito - yscorpion: @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/cD4LcrbU#8@@LinkEnd@@  Edit 2: Bonus fun fact!  Chessable member Indre found a modern game where this exact same tactic occurred between two 2500+ masters.  See?  Anyone can fall for these tactics if you aren't vigilant!  Ibragimov - Zhelinin, Moscow 1998: @@LinkStart@@https://www.redhotpawn.com/chess/grandmaster-games/viewmastergame.php?pgnid=76021@@LinkEnd@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
