[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Weakness on f7 12"]
[Result "*"]

{ Holzhausen - Tarrasch, Hamburg 1910   It pains me to include this one, as Tarrasch is my favourite player, but he walked into this one. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ We've seen this before; Black defends  e5  but at the cost of restricting his Bishop. }
3. Bc4 Be7 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ 5.Qxd4  is less good, as  5...Nc6  wins time. TIME IS EVERYTHING. } 5... Nf6
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. O-O O-O
{ All the same, both sides are playing by standard opening principles: developing and castling. }
8. h3
{ At first glance this is an unnecessary pawn move, and it is, but it's also an advanced idea.  If development is the main goal, part of that includes stopping your opponent from developing.  Here, White denies Black's Bishop the  g4  -square, and if the Bishop doesn't go there, where does it go? }
8... Re8 9. Re1 Nd7
{ Given this is a tactical puzzle, the first move is perhaps obvious, but can you find the follow-up? }
10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Ne6
{ The star move. Her Majesty is trapped, and the Black King is lured further to his doom. Strangely, even with all the Black pieces nearby, the King is defenceless. }
11... Kxe6 12. Qd5+ Kf6 13. Qf5#
{ Sacrifices on  f7  are extremely common and extremely powerful. If it is available, it's always worth spending a moment on Bxf7, because if it works, you could win a pawn or you could win the King.  Also, don't worry: Tarrasch will reappear and in a much more flattering light }
