[SetUp "1"]

{ Beginners sometimes wonder why castling is so important. The previous section on Bxf7 sacrifices, almost all against uncastled Kings, give a pretty convincing answer. Here is an even better one: the open e-file. A King in an open center in general, and on an open e-file in particular, is a serious disadvantage. If you are behind in development as well, it can be decisive. Here is the simplest example: }
1. Re1+
{ Black is now forced to block the check, and White can pile up the pressure. }
1... Be7 2. Nd5
{ and White can either exchange on  e7  immediately or play Qe2 first. Black will lose a piece here.   2.Qe2  is another common way of adding pressure, but it isn't as accurate here.  Kf8  Black steps off the e-file, breaking the pin.  3.Nd5  Bd6  Now the Bishop can move out of the way. We will see other positions where the Qe2 approach is best later on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nxe4
{ This is a relatively common position amongst very new players.  The e-file opens immediately, and White can take advantage. }
4. Qe2 { Now if the Knight moves... } 4... Nf6
{ White can now use one of the strongest ideas in chess: the discovered check.  White's Knight can move anywhere, and then White's Queen will give check.  Since Black MUST do something about the check, the Knight is free to go wherever it pleases.  The best square is: }
5. Nc6+
{ White wins the Queen.  Discovered checks are often extremely strong, and discovered checks delivered on the open e-file to the uncastled King are frequently decisive.  A close cousin, the discovered double-check, often immediately mates!  If you can set one up, it is almost always worth it.  Let's look at several examples. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 3"]
[Result "*"]

{ Meek - NN, New Orleans 1855   This is a funny game. In fact, most games played in the 1800s between 'Actual Name' and 'NN' tend to be fun games. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxe4 5. Nxe4
{ The e-file is immediately open. } 5... Bg4 { Black ignores the open e-file. }
6. Qe2 { White now sets a one-move trap, and Black falls into it. } 6... Bxf3
{ If you recaptured on  f3  here automatically, do a one-minute plank as penance, all the while repeating 'I will not ignore a discovered double-check on the e-file, I will not ignore a discovered double-check on the e-file,' for the entire 60 seconds. }
7. Nf6#
{ Both the White Queen and Knight are attacked, but because it's double check, it doesn't matter. Instead, it's mate ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Sanders - NN, New York 1910  This is an even funnier game, because Black, an unknown amateur, is completely winning until he walks into a mate in two. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 exf4
{ Black spends time opening the e-file and not developing. } 5. Bc4 Qh4+ 6. g3
{ This move should lose, but it sets up a fiendish trap. } 6... fxg3 7. Qe2
{ White seizes the e-file... } 7... g2+
{ Black uses a discovered check to win the Rook. He just needs to not ignore the discovered double-check waiting on the e-file. }
8. Kd1 gxh1=Q
{ And Black ignored it...   8...Bg4  Black could have won instantly with this move, pinning the Queen.   8...Be6  or this move, blocking the e-file  9.Bxe6  gxh1=Q  and now there's no discovered check.   8...Be7  or even just this move. Only unbridled greed 'MUST WIN ROOK NAOW!' could lose this position for Black. }
9. Nf6+
{ If you are unfamiliar with the power of the discovered double-check on the e-file, it's easy to look at this position, see White is down a truckload of material and just resign. A better idea, though, is to give mate. }
9... Kd8 10. Qe8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 5"]
[Result "*"]

{ Young Smithy - 'Humre', Internet 2004   The following idea is one I've used several times in the King's Gambit. This is the simplest example. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 d5
{ This is a good idea: Black is fighting for the center. } 4. exd5 Qxd5
{ This is a less good idea, though: White can develop with tempo against the Queen.   4...Nf6  and taking back with the Knight is better. }
5. Nc3 Qe6+
{ Black tries to use the open e-file, but White has an interesting try that contains a drop of poison. }
6. Kf2
{ White steps off the e-file and prepares a devastating Re1. Putting the Queen on the open e-file can be very good, but if YOUR King is still there, it can also be very bad.   6.Qe2  or  6.Be2  are also good, but they don't give you a chance to win instantly. }
6... Nf6 { Note that  6...Bc5  just runs into  7.d4. } 7. Bb5+
{ White develops with tempo. } 7... c6 { 7...Kd8  is ugly but forced. } 8. Re1
{ And now the Rook slides over and wins the Queen. This is a very powerful idea to remember: if the King and Queen are ever on the same file, you want to put a Rook there as fast as possible. }
