[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 6"]
[Result "*"]

{ Smithy - 'sompon', Internet 2004  This full game will be analyzed in, get this, the Complete Game section. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. c4 c6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd3 Qe7+
{ For now, let's look at the themes: Black tries to use the open e-file, but White can block it while developing his minor pieces. }
7. Ne2 Nf6 8. O-O { White has castled, which means Black must watch for Re1. }
8... Be6 9. Nf4 dxc4 10. Nxe6 fxe6
{ The e-file is now closed, but the King and Queen are still in a dangerous situation. }
11. Bxc4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 b5
{ Whenever you see the enemy King and Queen on the e-file, your first thought should be, 'Can I open the e-file and take advantage ?' }
13. Bxe6
{ Yes, we can ! If Black recaptures then the e-file will be his downfall. }
13... Qxe6
{ The e-file is now open, and our Rook can slide over.  In the game, Black played   13...Na6  and soon fell to a powerful attack. }
14. Re1 Qxe1+
{ 14...Ne4  Black can block the e-file with his Knight, but White can then attack and win the Knight instead.  15.Qf3   15.f3  also works, but using the Queen stops Black from castling.  15...Kd8  16.Rxe4  White has regained his material and Black's King is stuck in the center. }
15. Qxe1+
{ Having the King and Queen lined up is a recipe for disaster  (or victory !)  , so always look out for that. }
