[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 7"]
[Result "*"]

{ Angel - Buschke, New York 1940   This game shows how occupying the open e-file may not do anything instantly, but it can still be potent later on. }
1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nf3 d6 4. d4 Bg4 5. Be2 c5 6. O-O Qb6
{ Up til now, both sides have been developing, but now Black brings his Queen out early. }
7. exd6 { White sees that and immediately opens the e-file. } 7... exd6
{ 7...Qxd6  Taking with the Queen keeps the e-file closed but would cost Black a tempo, as his Queen moves twice. }
8. Re1
{ White immediately seizes the open file, and Black starts getting worried. }
8... Be7 { Black tries to block the e-file. } 9. Bc4
{ White moves the Bishop again, but it attacks the  Nd5  , forcing Black to lose time, and also lets the Rook control the e-file. Black can't castle or he loses the  Be7  . }
9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nf6 11. Nc3
{ White continues development. Black still can't castle because  Be7  hangs, and he can't move the Bishop because of the pin on the e-file. }
11... Nc6 12. Nd5 Qd8
{ Black tries to keep everything defended, but White can take advantage of the e-file in a different way.   12...Nxd5  13.Bxd5  And White is attacking both  f7  and pressuring the e-file. Black still can't castle because  O-O  14.Bxc6  bxc6  15.Rxe7  loses the Bishop anyway. }
13. Qxf6
{ White has so many pieces near the Black King, of course there's a tactic ... and it's a darn pretty one !   13.Nxf6+  gxf6  14.Qxf6  is also strong, but if you can sacrifice your Queen, you have to do it. }
13... gxf6 14. Nxf6+ { The Knight is immune because of the pin. } 14... Kf8 15.
Bh6#
{ A minor piece mate ! The e-file might not give you an immediate gain, but it is always good to occupy it. The longer the enemy King stays in the center, the more powerful it becomes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 8"]
[Result "*"]

{ Shoup - Marshall, Sioux City 1906 } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ White immediately opens the center. I especially like this strategy. } 3...
exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 { 5.Bd3 ??  Playing this first doesn't work.  Nxd4 }
5... bxc6 6. Bd3 Rb8
{ We generally want to develop our minor pieces before we develop our major pieces. Black is in danger of falling behind in development. }
7. Bg5 d5
{ 7...Rxb2 ?  The goal of the opening isn't to win pawns ! It's to develop !  8.e5  White is doing even better than in the game, as he has a massive lead in development. }
8. e5 Qe7 { Risky. Black uses the e-file, but his King and Queen are in line. }
9. O-O Qxe5 10. Re1
{ Seizing the e-file. This doesn't win the Queen because Black can interject his Knight. }
10... Ne4
{ Black is hanging on by a thread, but White needs to be careful as well because his  Bg5  is hanging. }
11. Bxe4
{ White immediately attacks the e-file.   11.f3  is weaker because Black can take on  g5  guilt-free.  Qxg5  12.fxe4  Bc5+  Developing with tempo !  13.Kh1  O-O  Black is castled, has good development and is even a pawn up. }
11... Qxg5
{ 11...Be6  Black had to find this move to stay in the game, where the Bishop blocks the e-file and Black will win back his piece next move.  If you think this is not an easy move to find, you are right, and this shows the problem: the longer you leave your King in the center, the harder the moves you'll have to find to stay safe. }
12. Bxd5+ { White opens the e-file with check. } 12... Be7 13. Bxc6+ Kf8
{ White has a good position with normal moves, but in a position like this, with White dominating the center and the Black King very vulnerable, we should look to see if there is a knockout. There is, and it's beautiful. }
14. Qd8+
{ The Bishop is deflected off the e-file, allowing decisive penetration. }
14... Bxd8 15. Re8#
{ Black voluntarily opened the e-file and put his King and Queen in line. White simply used that e-file against him. }
