[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Open e-file 9"]
[Result "*"]

{ Kieninger - Mross, Munich 1941 } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5.
Nc3 a6 6. g3 b5
{ Black is making a lot of pawn moves, so he has to be very careful. } 7. Bg2
Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Re1
{ White immediately puts his Rook on the e-file. This is smart because Black cannot castle quickly. }
9... e6 10. e5 { White tries to immediately open the center. } 10... Bxg2 11.
exf6 Bb7 12. fxg7
{ 12.Nxe6  This sacrifice is also strong.  fxe6  13.Rxe6+  Kf7  14.fxg7  Bxg7  15.Rxd6  White will win back his piece with a lot of extra pawns, and the Black King is very unhappy. }
12... Bxg7 13. Nf5
{ Sacrificing on  e6  immediately is stronger. This allows Black to castle out of it. }
13... Bf8
{ Black thinks he's okay because the e-file isn't open yet. Opps.   13...O-O  14.Nxg7  Kxg7  15.Qxd6  White has won a pawn, but Black is still alive.  When you have a Rook on the e-file against an uncastled King, always look to open the center. If it works, you win instantly. }
14. Rxe6+ { White now wins instantly. } 14... Be7
{ 14...fxe6  Taking is immediate death.  15.Qh5#  Destruction on the light-diagonal. We'll see this theme in-depth in the next section. }
15. Nxd6+
{ Again using the e-file ! White has many strong moves, but this is thematic and best. }
15... Kf8 16. Bh6+ { Developing with tempo. } 16... Kg8 17. Qg4+
{ Developing with tempo again ! The e-file was the start of this decisive attack, which will mate in a few moves. If the e-file isn't open yet, see if you can open it ! The attack's then often play themselves.    Black resigned without allowing the mate:  17...Bg5  18.Re8+  Nf8  19.Rxf8+  Qxf8  20.Qxg5  Qg7  21.Qxg7# }
