[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The Open e-file 10"]
[Result "*"]

{ norocosul - SmithyQ, Chess.com 2015  An example from one of my games will finish this section off. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Both sides develop, and here I pin his Knight, indirectly threatening  e4  . }
6. Nxc6
{ White needs to exchange Knights before defending with   6.Bd3 ??  , as  Nxd4  wins a piece. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 { I strike out at the center, securing a good game. } 8.
Bd2 { White develops meekly. } 8... O-O 9. a3
{ Now White makes a poor pawn move, falling behind in development when his King is in the center. Uh oh. }
9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 dxe4 { White can try to win his pawn back, but } 11. Bxf6
Qxf6 12. Bxe4
{ White hasn't castled yet and the e-file is open.  Show how Black can take advantage. }
12... Re8
{ White has delayed in castling, and he must now defend awkwardly on the e-file.  If he could castle without losing material, though, he'd be fine.   Though my move was both natural and the computer's first choice,  12...Qe5  is simple and strong as well. After  13.Qe2  Re8  , Black will play  f5  next and win the Bishop directly. }
13. f3 Ba6
{ Extremely powerful. White cannot castle through check, which means his King can't leave the e-file. }
14. c3 Rad8
{ Developing the last piece with tempo before starting the decisive attack. At amateur level, so many games are lost because we try to attack before finishing development. When you can finish development with tempo, you do it, end of story. }
15. Qc1
{ In positions like this, if we can attack the pinned Bishop with our f-pawn, we'll win it. First, we need to move our Queen, ideally with tempo, and then we can play f5. }
15... Qh4+ { Checking is moving with tempo ! } 16. g3 Qh3
{ Another move with tempo, as the threat is Qg2 and the Rook is trapped. } 17.
Qc2 { White defends against one threat, but now we can win the Bishop. } 17...
f5 18. Kf2 fxe4
{ In this final position, not only are we up material, but we are up in time as well. This is because White was forced to defend passively on the open e-file. We could then finish development and attack, and White couldn't resist. When you get one advantage  (open e-file)  , it often leads to another  (a lead in development)  , and that's when you can cash in. The rest of the game is below for reference. }
19. f4 e3+ 20. Kf3 Qh5+ 21. Kg2 Rd2+ 22. Qxd2 exd2 23. Rhf1 Bxf1+
{ SmithyQ won by resignation. } *

