[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 3"]
[Result "*"]

{ Damant - NN, London 1932 } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6
{ This lets White's center march on. Better is to take first.   3...dxe4  4.Bxe4  Nf6  Now the Knight develops with tempo and he's doing fine. }
4. e5 { Pushing forward with tempo, asking the Knight where it wants to go. }
4... Nfd7 5. e6
{ White keeps jamming this pawn down Black's throat. If he takes... } 5... fxe6
{ Then the King's Diagonal is open, and that's decisive. } 6. Qh5+ g6 7. Qxg6+
{ If you can sacrifice your Queen, do it ! } 7... hxg6 8. Bxg6#
{ In this example, White FORCED Black's f-pawn to move, exposing the King's Diagonal. Combined with a lead in development, this can be extremely powerful. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Greco - NN, Rome 1619 } 1. e4 b6 2. d4 Bb7
{ Developing your Bishops like this is fine, but notice that White gets complete control of the center, and it's easier for White to continue developing next. }
3. Bd3 f5
{ Black plays a 'trap', trying to win material. What is more important, material or time ? }
4. exf5 Bxg2 { Black traps the Rook, but his King's Diagonal is wide open. } 5.
Qh5+ g6 6. fxg6
{ Black's defences on this diagonal have now been completely stripped, and he is in grave danger. }
6... Nf6
{ Black tries to develop with tempo against White's Queen, which would normally be good ... but ...   6...Bg7  7.gxh7+  Kf8  This lets Black live a bit longer, but White has a large advantage. }
7. gxh7+
{ Black's King is more important !    7.g7+  Nxh5  8.gxh8=Q  is also good, but mate is mate. }
7... Nxh5 8. Bg6#
{ Even a solitary Bishop is enough to produce mate. This is why you shouldn't be scared of sacrificing material; if the opponent's King's Diagonal is vulnerable, go for it, because it can be decisive. We will now look at some less obvious examples. }
