[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 5"]
[Result "*"]

{ Teed - Delmar, New York 1896 } 1. d4 f5
{ Black fights for the center, but he does it while in the King's Diagonal tactical section of this opening course ... hmm... }
2. Bg5 { White's idea is to prevent Black's natural Nf6. } 2... h6
{ 2...Nf6  3.Bxf6  exf6  and Black's pawn structure is ugly. } 3. Bf4 g5
{ Black is chasing the Bishop, but his King's Diagonal is now wide open. } 4.
Bg3 f4 { Is the Bishop trapped ? } 5. e3
{ Yes, the Bishop is trapped, but now the Queen is threatening mate on  h5  . }
5... h5
{ Black is having fun pushing pawns. Now the Rook controls  h5  , and the Bishop is threatened again. }
6. Bd3 { Now the Bishop is threatening the mate. } 6... Rh6
{ Again the Rook prevents the mate ... but that means the Rook is protecting against two different mates on two different squares. We call that overloaded, and White can capitalize immediately. }
7. Qxh5+ { Luring the Rook away from  g6  . } 7... Rxh5 8. Bg6#
{ And that's mate ! Perhaps it shouldn't be a surpise Black fell victim on the King's Diagonal, as Black spent the entire game only moving his Kingside pawns and a single Rook. }
