[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 6"]
[Result "*"]

{ Palau - Nollman, Europe 1930 } 1. d4 f5 2. e4
{ Black moves his f-pawn early, so White tries to smash him early. He isn't worried about giving up a pawn, because time is everything. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 d6 5. f3 exf3 6. Nxf3
{ By accepting the pawn, Black is up material but worryingly behind in development. }
6... Bg4 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Qe2 c6
{ Black makes a non-developing pawn move, and that lets White's time advantage grow further. }
9. Ne4
{ White takes advantage of his development lead, and now he threatens to win on  f6  or  d6  . }
9... Nxe4
{ 9...d5  If Black does nothing, then it's the e-file that brings about his doom.  10.Nd6#  Black can't take because of the pin, and his King is smothered. }
10. Qxe4 Bxf3 11. Qg6+
{ If you automatically recaptured on  f3  , go for a 1km run while constantly repeating, 'The King's Diagonal is key !' As long as the King is uncastled, ANY weakness on the King's Diagonal should be a warning. If a tactic works there, you win, so take a moment to look. }
11... hxg6 12. Bxg6#
{ White combined threats on the e-file to then take advantage of the King's Diagonal. This is incredibly common; rarely does one threat win by itself, but combining them works very well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 7"]
[Result "*"]

{ Kunitz - Salamon, Tanger 1907 } 1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. f3 exf3 4. Nxf3
{ White has sacrified a pawn but gets a lead in time. In the opening, these are called 'gambits,' and they can be very powerful. }
4... Bg4 5. Be3 Nc6 6. c3
{ White makes a non-developing pawn move, and now Black can strike out. } 6...
e5
{ Black strikes in the center, securing a good game. White isn't even ahead in development anymore, so Black is simply a pawn up. }
7. d5 Nce7 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qe4 { What is more important, time or material ? }
9... f6
{ Black plays this ugly move so he doesn't lose his e-pawn ... but he is already up a pawn ! He could have played for time !   9...Nf6 !  Black can return the pawn but gain time attacking the Queen, just like the very first lesson of the course ! If they had Chessable in 1907, Black could have tried this idea.  10.Qxe5  Ng4  Improving the Knight, attacking the Queen and Bishop.  11.Qe4  Bf5  Developing with tempo again. The Queen will run around, Black's pieces are better, and  d5  (is a major weakness. Black is dominating. Why ? Because time is everything !) }
10. Bd3 { White sets up his only possible threat ... } 10... Ng6
{ ... and poor Black falls for it.   Something like  10...Bf5  , hitting the Queen and preparing  Qd7  with eventual Queenside castling, would give Black a simple advantage. }
11. Qxg6+ hxg6 12. Bxg6+ Ke7 13. Bc5#
{ Black was better up until move 10 ... but he made a mistake. And when you make a mistake with a weak King's Diagonal, that can be game. Don't make Black's mistake ! Always be mindful of your King's Diagonal. }
