[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 8"]
[Result "*"]

{ Gibaud - Lazard, Paris 1924   Poor White. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nd2
{ Don't hinder your own development.  The Knight on  d2  blocks the Bishop and Queen.  Sure, it doesn't seem like much now, but... }
2... e5
{ Black plays actively; he'll either win this pawn back or White will need to spend a lot of time to defend it. }
3. dxe5 Ng4
{ It's never too early to worry about your King's Diagonal.  You're saying, 'Smithy, what are you talking about?  There's no weakness on the King's Diagonal?'  True, no weakness ... yet. }
4. h3
{ As we saw in the last example, moving the h-pawn can fatally weaken the King's Diagonal. Now Black just needs to find the right sacrifice... }
4... Ne3
{ The Queen is trapped by her own pieces, and if White takes...   4...Nxf2  If you played this, did you calculate or just jump in because it looked thematic ?  5.Kxf2  Qh4+  6.g3  Qd4+  7.Kg2  White's King is safe, he's up material and after Nf3, he'll hit the Queen and be up in development. ALWAYS DOUBLE-CHECK YOUR TACTICS ! }
5. fxe3 { Ah, NOW we see the weakness, yes? } 5... Qh4+ 6. g3 Qxg3#
{ ANY Kingside pawn move can weaken the King's Diagonal. Yet another reason why we should be careful with pawn moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 9"]
[Result "*"]

{ Harry Nelson Pillsbury - NN, Toronto 1899   As a side note, the games of Harry Nelson Pillsbury are EXCELLENT for beginner's to study. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ White blocks in his  c1  -Bishop, but so did Black. White plans on castling quickly and then playing e4 to free the Bishop. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3 Nbd7 5. O-O b6
{ We noticed that White's plan to develop his Bishop was with a quick e4.  Black plans to develop it on the long diagonal.  It doesn't look that special right now, but if White does play e4, then the center pawns will be exchanged and the Bishop will be quite nice. }
6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. e4
{ We can see Pillsbury's plan has worked: he has excellent development and control of the center, and now his  c1  -Bishop is free to move... or at least it will be once he moves his Knight. }
7... dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bb7
{ We now know that Bishops are often a little stronger than Knights in most positions, but in the 1800s many preferred Knights. Pillsbury will show us why we should respect the Bishops. }
9. Nxd6+ cxd6 10. Bf4 Bxf3
{ Black gives up both Bishops and gives White a noticeable lead in time. } 11.
Qxf3 d5
{ We can see Black's idea: he has the Knights, so he is trying to block the position up. Unfortunately, he has no development and hasn't castled. }
12. Bd6 { And now Black can't castle ! } 12... Rc8 13. Rfe1 Rc6
{ Black tries to chase the Bishop away, but of course it stays on the annoying diagonal. }
14. Ba3 a5 15. c4
{ Black makes another pawn move, falling further behind in time, so White gets ready to open the position. Especially deadly with the King stuck in the center. }
15... Ne4 16. cxd5 Ng5
{ Black tries dancing with his Knights, but lone pieces can't fight White's entire army. }
17. Qg3 Rc8 18. dxe6 Nxe6
{ The e-file is now completely open. Sure,  d5  wins a piece, but can we do better ? }
19. Rxe6+ { First the e-file cashes in. } 19... fxe6
{ ... and as a result the King's Diagonal is weakened. } 20. Qg6+
{ If you can sacrifice your Queen, do it ! } 20... hxg6 21. Bxg6#
{ A beautiful game by Pillsbury. Another example of how one idea  (open e-file)  can transfer to another  (the weakened King's Diagonal)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 10"]
[Result "*"]

{ Tarrasch - Kurschner, Nuremberg 1893   Dr. Tarrasch is my favourite player, and he is perhaps the best player to study to learn not only basic opening play but positional play in general. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6
{ Black could take first   3...dxe4  4.Bxe4  because then  Nf6  would come with tempo. Always be on the lookout for winning tempi like this. }
4. e5 { Instead, White pushes ahead with tempo on the Knight. } 4... Nfd7 5.
Nf3 c5 6. c3
{ Both of these are pawn moves, but in blocked positions, pawn moves are often necessary. Here Black is attacking White's center and White is defending it. We know that the center is important, so these are good moves. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O f6
{ This is scary, though, weakening the King's Diagonal while down in development. }
8. Re1 f5
{ Black realizes that he is so far behind in development that he needs to keep the position closed. }
9. Be3 c4 { But seriously, this is a lot of pawn moves. } 10. Bc2 Be7 11. b3
{ Theory of Time: when ahead in development, push pawns to open the position. Watch how Tarrasch transforms this blocked center into moving magma. }
11... b5 12. a4 bxa4
{ 12...a6 ?  Black would normally want to play this, but he is too far behind in development.  13.axb5  axb5 ??  14.Rxa8  Opps. If Black had developed his Bishop, his Rook would have been protected and he would have been fine. }
13. bxc4 dxc4 14. d5
{ Time is everything ! White is ahead in development, and he now offers a pawn to completely open the game. }
14... Ncxe5
{ If   14...exd5  then  15.Bxa4  Bb7  16.Qxd5  and White is dominating everywhere. }
15. dxe6 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Nb6
{ Black is temporarily up a pawn, but he is six-thousand moves behind in development and his King is square in the crosshairs. }
17. Qxf5 Bf6 18. Bc5
{ Similar to the Pillsbury game, the Bishop stops Black from castling, and the finishing blow is identical as well.   18.Qh5+  is also good, kudos if you found this continuation:  g6  19.Bxg6+  hxg6  20.Qxg6+  Ke7  21.Bc5+  wins the Queen and mate soon after. }
18... Bb7 19. Qg6+ { If you can sacrifice the Queen, do it ! } 19... hxg6 20.
Bxg6#
{ Black fell behind in development, but he thought he was safe because the position was blocked. Tarrasch blew the game open, and the weakened King's Diagonal from Black's 7th move decided it in the end. }
