[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 11"]
[Result "*"]

{ Demby - Cohen, London 1932  Let's take everything we've learned so far and put it together ! }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ Black is making a lot of pawn moves and needs to be very careful. } 5. Be2
Qc7 6. O-O Nf6 7. Nc3 d5
{ Black has two pieces developed and his King is still in the center; White has three pieces and is already castled. Opening the center is a near suicidal decision. }
8. Re1
{ 8.exd5  This was more accurate, as  Nxd5  9.Nxd5  exd5  directly opens the e-file. }
8... dxe4 { Black wins a pawn... } 9. Bg5
{ ... but White is fully developed. Time is everything. } 9... Nd5
{ Black was worried about Bxf6, but this moves a piece twice when already behind in development. }
10. Nxe4 Nd7
{ This is an excellent combination, using everything we've learned so far. }
11. Nxe6 { Beautiful, opening the King's Diagonal. } 11... fxe6 12. Bh5+
{ The Bishop moves with tempo, which clears the e-file of one piece. } 12... g6
13. Qxd5 { Now we offer the Queen ! } 13... exd5 14. Nd6#
{ And a double-check on the e-file secures the game. Wow. When you look at this combo, it looks amazing, almost too amazing.   'How am I supposed to find this in my own games ?'   I agree, but it's really just two ideas: the King's Diagonal and the Open e-file. If you know these like the back of your hand, it only takes a little calculation to connect them together and win brilliantly. It's not easy, but it's not impossible.   As I said in the Introduction, this isn't just a 'basic' course, it is a foundational course. If you fully absorb these ideas, you have the foundation for amazing things ahead. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The King's Diagonal 12"]
[Result "*"]

{ GrahamT - Smithy, Internet 2004   Young Smithy will show us how it's done ... sorta. Historically, my first ever King hunt, so that's neat. }
1. f4 { White starts with f4, which immediately weakens the King's Diagonal. }
1... e5 { Since Time is everything, I offer a pawn to try to take advantage. }
2. fxe5 d6 3. exd6 Bxd6
{ For only one pawn, Black has a wide open position and a weak diagonal to attack. }
4. Nf3 g5
{ And I'm really attacking ! This is a dangerous move but likely not the best one. }
5. g3
{ Had White made a nothing move like  5.Nc3  , then  5...g4  6.Nd4  Qh4+  7.g3  Qxg3+  8.hxg3  Bxg3#  is the idea. }
5... g4 6. Nh4 Nc6
{ White has only one piece developed, a Knight on the side of the board, whereas Black has two and more coming fast. }
7. Bg2 f5
{ The wrong plan: I don't have enough development to push pawns and open the game. }
8. e3 Ne5
{ Now Young Smithy moves a piece twice, falling behind in time even though I've sacrificed a pawn for that time ! }
9. d4
{ 9.O-O  White could just castle, secure his King, and only then play  d4  and/or  e4  because then it's MY King that would be in trouble  ! }
9... Ng6 10. Nxg6 hxg6
{ This was my plan: the open h-file introduces some tactics on the weakened King's Diagonal. }
11. a3
{ White has moved mostly pawns and his King is weakened.  Can we take advantage? }
11... Rxh2 { Boom ! } 12. Kf2
{ White tries to keep things together.   12.Rxh2  Bxg3+  13.Kf1  Bxh2  Black won a pawn and White's King is forever weak. }
12... Bxg3+
{ and now the second blow ! Pulling the King into the open is often decisive. }
13. Kxg3 Qh4+ 14. Kf4 g5+
{ Young Smithy missed this move, so if you calculated it correctly you're farther ahead than I was !   14...g3+  In the actual game, I played an equally winning but much longer continuation.  15.Ke5  Qf6+  16.Kf4  Qd6+  17.Kf3  Qd5+  18.Kxg3  Qxg2+  I had held my breath the entire time. Now I had regained my piece and could relax.  19.Kf4  g5+  20.Ke5  Qe4#  King Hunts are fun ! A decade later and I've never forgotten this one. }
15. Ke5
{ The King is in the center, so now we just need to find one hard move to finish him off. }
15... Qh6
{ In these types of positions, ask yourself, 'If my Queen could be placed anywhere, where would it go ?' Well, Qd6 or Qe6 would be mate, so let's re-arrange the Queen to go to those squares. That's how you find this maneuver. }
16. Kd5 { 16.Rxh2  or anything else is mate in one.  Qe6# } 16... Qc6+ 17. Ke5
Qd6#
{ Sometimes the King's Diagonal doesn't lead to immediate mate. Sometimes it merely flushes the King out and you have to deliver mate mid-board. }
*

