[FEN "r2qkb1r/2p2p1p/p2p4/1p2p1p1/3nP1b1/1BNP1N2/PPP2P1K/R1BQ1R2 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Do you remember this position from earlier?  What should White play? } 1.
Nxe5
{ There are two possibilities.   If you played  1.Nxe5  aiming for a Legal Mate, congratulations, you are awesome!   If you played  1.Bxf7+  , aiming for the standard  f7  -sacrifice after  1...Kxf7  2.Ng5+  , congratulations, you played the same losing combination as Lasker's opponent!  2...Qxg5!  3.Bxg5  Bxd1  and Black is up material. ALWAYS DOUBLE CHECK YOUR TACTICS! }
1... Bxd1
{ 1...dxe5  2.Qxg4  and White has not only won a pawn, but also got rid of the annoying pin. }
2. Bxf7+ Ke7 3. Nd5#
{ In tactical positions, there are often several different ideas, and it's so important to accurately calculate.  Here, the standard Bxf7+ loses, whereas the Legal Mate wins.  It's not enough to notice a common motif; we need to accurately calculate it as well. }
