[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Noah's Ark 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Bb5
{ Bishops are long-range pieces, and they are the most likely piece to get trapped by pawns.  One particular motif is known as the Noah's Ark Trap, where a Bishop is corralled by on-rushing pawns. }
2... a6 3. Ba4
{ The Bishop retreats to an 'active' square, but now the pawns come with tempo. }
3... b5 4. Bb3 c4
{ The Bishop is completely hemmed in and is thus lost.  The trap is named such because the three Black pawns resemble the shape of an ark ... if you use your imagination.  Whatever you call it, be careful with your Bishops early on, especially if your opponent's pawns are mobile. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Noah's Ark 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bb4 4. c3 Ba5 5. a4
{ It helps to be sneaky when trying to set-up the Noah's Ark Trap. The direct  5.b4  Bb6  6.a4  a6  wins time against our Bishop while also creating space for his own Bishop to retreat. Starting with the a-pawn instead hides our intention and may let our opponent overlook it. }
5... Nf6 { He does! } 6. b4 Bb6 7. a5
{ Now Black doesn't have time to play a6, as } 7... a6 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. axb6
{ He loses the piece anyway.  If your opponent advances his Rook's pawn early, be on the lookout for hidden Noah's Ark ideas. }
