[Black "Tactical Section - Long Diagonal 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. b4 { I'm a big fan of gambits, but this one is perhaps the worst. }
2... cxb4 3. a3 d5
{ Time is everything.  Rather than trying to win a pawn, Black strikes in the center. }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ Normally White would play Nc3 here, but his silly b4-move has left a Black pawn covering that square, so it's impossible. }
5. axb4
{ Early in the game, be very careful about moving the Knight's pawns  (the g- and b-pawns)  .  This opens the long diagonal and the Rook can be left hanging.  This is the simplest example. }
5... Qe5+ { Black both checks the King and attacks the undefended Rook. } 6.
Be2 Qxa1
{ This motif is especially common on the Queenside.  Be careful about moving the b-pawn, especially if you cannot immediately put your Bishop on the long diagonal.  A few more examples will drive the point home. }
