1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 b5
{ What's more important, developing your pieces or hanging onto a single extra pawn?  This is a trap many beginners fall into, because they care too much about material. }
4. a4
{ White attacks the pawn.    4.Qf3  first does not work because of  4...c6  , blocking the diagonal. We need to move the c-pawn first. }
4... c6 5. axb5
{ Black has moved his Queenside pawns, potentially exposing the long diagonal.  White now opens those lines. }
5... cxb5 6. Qf3
{ The diagonal is wide open and Black can't do anything to save his Rook.  Always be careful about moving those Knight pawns  (or, if your opponent does so, take care if you can take advantage)  . }
6... Nf6 7. Qxa8 *

