[Black "Tactical Section - Long Diagonal 3"]
[Result "*"]

{ Becker vs. Norman-Hansen, Munich 1936 } 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4
Nd7
{ Black prepares to play Nf6, so that he can recapture with his Knight instead of his Queen.  This is a very solid way of playing, with the only downside being his light-square Bishop, which is hard to develop immediately. }
5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Bd3 Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Nf6
{ Black is moving his Knight twice, but it goes to a better square and White needs to move his Bishop again.  On the whole, this is not a loss of time, as White must lose time as well. }
8. Bd3 Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Bg5
{ Up until now, both sides have played sensibly and according to principles.  Now, though, Black makes a tactical mistake. }
10... b6
{ This is similar to my error in the last example.  Black wants to place his Bishop on the long diagonal, where it would be excellent.  It looks safe now, but a simple exchange shows the downside. }
11. Bxf6
{ By exchanging the Knight, White removes Black's control over the  e4  -square. }
11... Bxf6 12. Qe4 { White hits both loose Rook as well as mate on  h7  . } *

