{ 'rhand' - Young Smithy, Internet 2001  Here's the earliest example in my database where I fall for this sort of tactic. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4
{ White is trying to open the position in the center. } 4... dxc4
{ This is a loss of time.  If I want to take the pawn, I should wait for the light-square Bishop to move first.   For example,  4...Nf6  5.Bd3  dxc4  6.Bxc4  is the same position as the game, but it's Black's turn to move. Black has thus gained time compared to the game. }
5. Bxc4 Nf6 6. Nc3 b6
{ My idea is to put my Bishop on this great diagonal.  Looks beautiful!  Unfortunately, Chessable nor this course existed back in 2001, so I didn't see what I was walking into to. }
7. Qf3 { Simply put, my Rook is trapped. } 7... Ba6
{ I found a tricky move, trying to get his Bishop in exchange for the Rook. }
8. Bxf7+
{ Best.  White gets a pawn and forces Black to give up castling.   8.Qxa8  is possible, but Black might have some compensation after  8...Bxc4.   8.Bxa6?  Nxa6  and the Queen defends the Rook. }
8... Kxf7 9. Qxa8
{ I was young and played a few more moves before resigning.  I include this partly because it's funny, partly because it shows how much I've improved over the years.  And it's all thanks to opening principles! }
9... Qxd4 10. Qxb8 Qg4 11. Qg3 Qc4 12. Nf3 Qd3 13. Ne5+
{ I didn't resign when I lost the Rook or the Knight, but losing the Queen was too much. }
