[Result "*"]

{ Mattison vs. Tartakover, Budapest 1926 } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 e6
{ Black does not waste time trying to defend his pawn, but instead prepares his own development. }
4. e3 c5
{ Strictly speaking this does not help development, but it does fight for the center and is thus a good idea. }
5. Nf3 a6 { That's a lot of pawn moves that don't help development, though. }
6. Bxc4 Nf6 7. O-O b5
{ We can see Black's idea: he played  a6  so that  b5  would come with tempo, and now he wants to develop his Bishop to  b7  . }
8. Be2 Nc6
{ This is dubious.  If you play b6 or b5 to fianchetto your Bishop, you should do it as soon as possible.  The longer you delay, the more potential tactics can appear on that weakened diagonal. }
9. dxc5 Qc7
{ Black avoids the Queen exchange.    There was nothing wrong with  9...Bxc5  10.Qxd8+  Nxd8 }
10. Nd4 { White prepares to fight for the long diagonal with Bf3. } 10... Bxc5
{ Black played b5 four moves ago and has ignored the long diagonal.  It now costs him. }
11. Nxc6
{ White clears the Knight out of the way, pulling the Queen into danger. }
11... Qxc6 12. Bf3 { The skewer picks up a whole Rook. } 12... Qc7
{ Blocking with  12...Nd5  doesn't help, as  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.Bxd5  skewers the Rook anyway. }
13. Bxa8
{ Black played b5 to bring his Bishop to  b7  , but then he never did, and the weakness on the long diagonal then did him in. }
