[Black "Tactical Section - Long Diagonal 6"]
[Result "*"]

{ Conrady - O'Sullivan, Dublin 1957  Black never catches up in development even well into the middlegame, partly because he is wasting time, partly because White makes it hard for him to do it. }
1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian is a very popular opening, but because  c5  doesn't help develop any of the minor pieces, Black must attend to his development very carefully. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ White opens the game immediately, where he hopes his easier development will give him attacking chances. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ We can see the difference clearly here: both sides have two Knights developed, but White's  d4  -Knight is better placed than either of Black's.  Also, White can develop either Bishop anywhere, whereas Black's dark-square Bishop requires further tempi to get active.  In exchange, Black has two center-pawns to White's one, so he has more future potential in the center.  This is what makes the Sicilian such a fascinating opening: it's quick development vs center control. }
6. Bg5
{ White continues to develop quickly and threatens to ruin Black's pawn structure. }
6... Qb6 { Black ignores it by developing his Queen instead! } 7. Bxf6 gxf6
{ By ruining Black's pawn structure, White is hoping that Black's Bishop never gets into the game. }
8. Nb3 Bg7
{ Black misses his chance here.  8...f5!  is best. Compare the position after  9.Bd3  fxe4  10.Bxe4  Bg7  , where the Bishop has a beautiful diagonal. Remember, development isn't just about MOVING our pieces, it's about getting them ACTIVE.   8...Bh6?  looks more active, but after  9.Qh5  the Bishop is undefended and needs to move again. }
9. Nd5
{ White takes advantage of Black's early Queen development to push her back, though simply Bd3 was fine. }
9... Qd8 10. c3 { 'An unnecessary pawn move, Smithy?'  Yup. } 10... O-O
{ 10...f5!  was again possible. } 11. Bd3
{ White finally finds the right idea.  This prevents Black's f5-advance and keeps the  Bg7  inactive. }
11... Ne5
{ Black now starts a faulty plan, where he moves the same piece 18 times instead of finishing development. }
12. O-O Kh8 13. Bc2 Nc4 14. Qh5
{ 14.Nd2!  is even better, trading White's worst piece for Black's best one. The pawn is immune, as 14 ...  Nxb2?  15.Qc1  traps the Knight. }
14... e6 15. Ne3 Nxe3 16. fxe3
{ We can see why 14.Nd2 was better: instead of trading his worst Knight, White was forced to trade his best Knight, and it ruined his pawn structure as well. }
16... Qe7 17. Qh4
{ I'm not entirely sure of White's idea here.  I think he's trying to set up a trap ... and Black falls into a trap, so I guess it works.  Rad1, bringing the last piece into the game, or Rf3, preparing a Rook lift to attack the King, make more sense. }
17... h6
{ Here's where I point out that on move 7 Black had two pieces developed, and here on move 17 he still has two pieces developed.  His Knight maneuver cost a LOT of time. }
18. Rad1 b6
{ Black's last move was b6, getting ready to develop his Bishop on the long diagonal.  What is White's best move? }
19. e5
{ We know the long diagonal can be very weak if his Bishop isn't yet there, so White prepares to occupy it immediately. }
19... dxe5 20. Qe4
{ The Queen slides over, threatening both mate on  h7  and the Rook in the corner.  This is technically a middlegame position, but because Black is so far behind in development, the typical opening tactics still appear! }
20... f5 { Black resigned rather than allow this. } 21. Qxa8
{ Game Source: Dodgy's Sicilian Tactics - 1000 Puzzles! on Chessable. } *

