{ This is a well-known trap in the Queen's Gambit, called the Cambridge Springs  (because it was first played at the Cambridge Springs tournament)  . }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. Nf3
{ Up until now, both sides have developed naturally.  Black now begins preparing an interesting idea to break the pin and get active play. }
5... c6 6. e3 Qa5
{ The Queen does not come with check, but she does put pressure on the fifth rank, and there's a nasty trap available if White blindly plays natural moves. }
7. Bd3
{ 7.cxd5  is the easiest move to play, as it prevents Black from opening the fifth-rank with tempo. }
7... Ne4
{ Black jumps in.  This moves a piece twice, but it attacks  c3  (the Knight is pinned)  , and the most natural move... }
8. Qc2 { ... defends  c3  , pressures  e4  , but it loses on the spot. } 8...
Nxg5 { First Black takes with the Knight. } 9. Nxg5 dxc4
{ Then he opens the fifth rank, simultaneously attacking two pieces.  White must lose material. }
10. Bxc4 Qxg5
{ Here the Qa5 did not come with check, but it's latent power across the fifth rank was still effective. }
