[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Discovery 2"]
[Result "*"]

{ 'DragonDude' - Young Smithy, Internet 2002  Here's an example of where I walk into a standard version of this trap. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Bc4
{ White's Bishop is on the aggressive diagonal, and Black needs to be careful. }
6... g6 { This is not careful. } 7. Nxc6 bxc6
{ This position is worth knowing, as it is a very common trap.  First, White blasts open the center while leading in development. }
8. e5 dxe5
{ Black doesn't have to take, but after something like  8...d5  9.exf6  dxc4  10.Qf3  White is in the driver's seat. }
9. Bxf7+
{ The idea is now clear: first White opened the d-file, and now he distracts the King. }
9... Kxf7 10. Qxd8
{ And I lost my Queen.  I learned from this game, though, and never fell for this trap again.  Even better, I've used it to win several games over the years in similar positions.  Learning the general principles and basic tactical patterns wins games! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Discovery 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 cxd4
{ These Queen Discovery tactics don't have to involve Bxf7.  Discovered attacks are also common, as in this well-known position. }
7. cxd4
{ Note that the most common error  7.Nxd4?  fails because of  Nxe5.  Don't forget about your pawn on  e5  (!) }
7... Nxd4
{ It looks like  d4  is inadequately defended, but there is a tactic. } 8. Nxd4
Qxd4 9. Bb5+
{ The discovered attack hits the Queen, winning it.  Whenever the Queen is undefended, such tactics are possible. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Discovery 4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Wren - Mayfield, Halifax 1941  A slightly different version of the standard idea. }
1. e4 Nf6
{ This is the Alekhine defence: Black gives up lots of space and moves his Knight around, but he tries to get tactical opportunities later on against White's center.  Not a recommended approach for beginners. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4
{ White has no pieces developed yet, but he completely owns the center. } 4...
d6 5. Bd3 dxe5 6. dxe5 N8d7
{ Black tries to attack White's pawns, but they just march forward. } 7. e6 Nf6
{ The first move is obvious, but what is the tactical idea afterwards? } 8.
exf7+ Kxf7 9. Bg6+
{ The Bishop clears the d-file with tempo, and the rival Queen is undefended. }
9... hxg6 10. Qxd8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Discovery 5"]
[Result "*"]

{ Warren vs. Selman, Corr. 1930  This may be the shortest decisive correspondence game ever. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ This is the Budapest opening.  Black sacrifices the  e5  -pawn, but he argues that his lead in development is extra valuable with White 'wasting' a move with  c4  . }
3. dxe5 Ne4 4. a3 { An unnecessary pawn move. } 4... d6 5. exd6 Bxd6
{ After five moves, White is up a pawn but has zero pieces developed.  He must be extremely careful. }
6. g3
{ This is a slightly more complicated version of our theme, but the core idea is the same: }
6... Nxf2
{ In the game White resigned here, likely to save money on postage.  If he takes the Knight, then ... }
7. Kxf2 Bxg3+
{ Now the Bishop can move with check!    7...Bc5+  is less precise, because after  8.Ke1  the King protects the Queen again. Black does have  8...Bf2+  9.Kxf2  Qxd1  , winning the Queen regardless, but the text is both faster and wins a pawn. }
8. hxg3 Qxd1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Trap 1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Frazer vs. Taubenhaus, Paris 1888  Exhibit A on why you don't want to bring your Queen out early. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ This is called the Steinitz variation, named after the First World Champion ... and it kinda sucks to have such a lousy opening named after yourself... }
5. Nc3 Nf6 { What do we do to Queens that develop too early? } 6. Nf5
{ We attack her, because Queens can be trapped easily in the opening. } 6...
Qh5
{ 6...Qg4  was better.  7.f3  Qg6  8.g4  Taking away squares and threatening to trap the Queen next move, so  8...h6  9.Nh4  Qh7  and the Queen is stuck on a terrible square completely out of the game, and meanwhile White can even start attacking with  10.Nb5  or  10.Bf4 }
7. Be2 Qg6 8. Nh4
{ The White pieces completely surround the Black Queen, and she has no safe squares.  In the opening, the abundance of pawns and pieces can cut off escape squares, and the Queen can be corralled very often. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Trap 2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Barnett vs. Eastwood, Corr. 1949  This is also the shortest, decisive correspondence game ever. }
1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 { Bringing the Queen out early is always risky. }
3... Qf6 { But here, Black decides to return the favour. } 4. Qe3 Nh6
{ Both sides are paying for their early Queen development: White's Queen blocks in his dark-square Bishop, whereas Black's Queen forces his Knight to develop to the side of the board. }
5. Nc3 Ng4 { Black then moves his Knight twice!  Yuck. } 6. Nd5
{ So White returns the favour!  What a game. } 6... Qc6
{ As a general rule, this is an extremely unsafe spot for the Queen: she can fall victim to Bb5 ideas, as we'll see. }
7. Qf4
{ White pressures  c7  , threatening a fork as well as the Knight; Black thinks his next move saves him, but ... }
7... d6 8. Bb5 { Black resigned.  His Queen is pinned, and if he takes it... }
8... Qxb5 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxb5
{ ... he loses to a fork.  Be very wary of moving your Queen out early, and especially wary of placing her on  c3  /  c6  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Trap 3"]
[Result "*"]

{ Wiesel vs. Weigel, Corr. 1923  There's something about correspondence games and having Queens get trapped... }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5
{ No surprise, but Queens are 1000% more likely to get trapped when they are developed early. }
3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3
{ White has a lead in development and threatens  b7  . } 6... Nc6
{ This natural move puts Black in huge trouble.  6...c6  , even though it's a non-developing pawn move, needed to be played. }
7. Bb5
{ White has lots of good moves, but this is best: immediately pressuring  c6  and threatening to win it. }
7... Qb6 { Black defends  c6  , but her Majesty has very few squares... } 8.
Nd5 { The Knight highlights exactly how few squares she has! } 8... Qa5
{ 8...Qxb5  would allow  9.Nxc7+  fork. Moving the Queen off a5-d8 diagonal would also allow the  c7  (fork.  Black tries to hold things together, but one last deflection decides things.) }
9. b4
{ The Queen is now forced to the forking square.  Black resigned without allowing : }
9... Qxb5 10. Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Nxb5
{ We know that  f7  is the weakest square on the board.  When the Queen moves early,  c7  also becomes extremely weak, and a Knight in particular wants to land there.  When thinking of Queen traps, or trying to take advantage of early Queen moves, keep an eye on  c7  , because tactics often work there. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Trap 4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hayndl vs. Crespi, Sarajevo 1925  It's high time we show a game where White gets his Queen trapped. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. Qf3
{ We can already see the seeds of potential destruction: bringing the Queen out early. }
6... Nc6 7. Nge2
{ This is likely the best square for the Knight, but it does block the Queen's potential retreat. }
7... Bd6 8. Bd2 e5
{ Black advances in the center and prepares Bg4, harassing the Queen with tempo. }
9. d5
{ When the Queen is developed early, your dominant thought should be, 'Can I attack it?  Can I develop with tempo?' }
9... Bg4
{ 9...e4?  is also thematic, but it doesn't work here. White can do  10.Nxe4!  , when  10...Bg4??  11.Nxf6+  is check, and after  11...Qxf6  12.Qxg4  White's Queen not only escapes, but she's up a piece as well.   Moving the Knight with  9...Na5?!  or may not be 'bad' but it completely misses the point. When your opponent develops his Queen early, your dominant thought should be, 'Can I develop with tempo against the Queen?' And that's especially true when the Queen has no retreat squares. }
10. Qg3 e4 { Now the Bishop joins the attack as well. } 11. Qh4 Ne5
{ The Knight goes to a great square while hitting the Bishop with tempo. } 12.
Bb3 Ng6
{ The Knight completes its journey, and the Queen only has one square left... }
13. Qg5 h6
{ ... and now she has zero.  Black focused all his energy on attacking the Queen and developing with tempo, and it worked wonders for him.  That's exactly how you should approach similar positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Queen Trap 5"]
[Result "*"]

{ Richardson vs. Eva, Hastings 1939  Black thinks he finds a nice tactic, but White sees one move further. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6
{ While this is a possible way of playing, it gives White a sizable central advantage. }
4. Be3 Bg7 5. Nf3 Nbd7
{ White's development tends to be more natural than Black's, precisely because of his central advantage. }
6. Qd2 Ng4 { Moving a piece twice in the opening, losing time. } 7. O-O-O Nxe3
8. Qxe3
{ Black has won the Bishop pair, but it took him several tempi to do it.  Is the purpose of the opening to win the Bishop pair? }
8... Nf6 { Moving the same piece again while already behind in development. }
9. h3
{ White arguably plays too timid here:  9.e5!  tries to open the position up and use that lead in development. }
9... e6 10. Nh4
{ White prepares f4 and e5, though again e5 immediately was a strong possibility. }
10... h5
{ ... I don't even know what this is.  Can you guys help me out?    'An unnecessary non-developing pawn move, Smithy?'  Thanks guys, that sounds right. }
11. f4 { White prepares his central domination, and Black gets too cute. }
11... Nxe4
{ Black thinks, thanks to the discovery on  h4  , that he is winning a pawn. }
12. Nxe4
{ If you played  12.Qxe4?  Qxh4  , you just justified Black's play. Please feel shame. }
12... Qxh4
{ Black has won a pawn, but his Queen is dangerously short on squares.  Hmm... }
13. Ng5
{ A lovely move.  The Knight physically blocks the Queen's retreat, and after the coming  g3  the lady is trapped.  This is a powerful idea, cutting off the Queen's escape BEFORE attacking her. }
