[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Punishing Greed 1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Muhlock vs. Kostics, 1912  This is a well-known trap, and this game is the first time it showed up in my database  (so it wasn't well-known to Muhlock!)  . }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nd4
{ You can see the appeal of this trap: it looks like a beginner move, moving a piece twice and hanging the  e5  -pawn.  It contains a ridiculous amount of poison, though. }
4. Nxe5
{ Just for the record, virtually any other legal move is better for White.  O-O, Nc3, c3, Nxd4, d3, even Kf1 is prolly better for White.  Well, maybe not, but the point stands: this is a terrible trap unless White gets greedy and grabs the pawn.  Say it with me: THE OPENING IS NOT ABOUT WINNING MATERIAL. }
4... Qg5 { Black counterattacks the Knight and the  g2  -pawn. } 5. Nxf7
{ White goes hyper-greed, cashing in on  f7  ... and now loses. } 5... Qxg2 6.
Rf1 Qxe4+ 7. Be2 Nf3#
{ Time is everything.  If you focus on winning material, you will inevitably fall into traps like this one.  I would hate for that to happen.  Focus on developing first and foremost. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - Punishing Greed 2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Adams vs. Kramer, New York 1946  White's eyes light up and he wins a pawn ... but without finishing development.  Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3 Bxd3 5. Qxd3
{ After this exchange of Bishops, White's Queen is developed early, but it's hard for Black to attack her, so it should be fine ... unless the Queen goes charging like Rambo up the board. }
5... e6 6. Ne2
{ The Knight looks more natural on  f3  , but White wants to keep the option of playing f4 on the table, and the Knight may go to  g3  and help prepare the f5-push in the middlegame.  Since the Queen is already on  d3  and the Bishop was previously traded, the Knight does not hinder White's development, so it is an interesting idea. }
6... c5 7. c3 Ne7 { Up until now, it's a normal position. } 8. Qb5+
{ White now gets greedy and sees that he can win the  c5  -pawn. } 8... Qd7
{ Blocking with the Knight lets White get what he wants:  8...Nbc6  9.Qxb7  Rb8  10.Qa6  and the Queen won't be trapped. Black has compensation for the pawn, but he can do better. }
9. Qxc5 Nf5
{ This  (or any other Knight move)  opens up the attack on the Queen, who is suddenly lacking any good squares. }
10. Qa5 b6
{ And the Queen is trapped.  Don't try to win pawns, kids.  Just finish development.  Virtually every example in the Annotated Game section, as well as many of the game fragments in this Tactical section, show one side being greedy and the other punishing him for it, so I won't dwell on this in detail.  Just remember, Time is everything.  Don't make winning material be your primary focus. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The Pawn Fork Trick 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5 { This is the simplest example of this trick. }
4. Nxe5 { White sac's the Knight ... } 4... Nxe5 5. d4
{ ... but wins it right back. } 5... Bd6 6. dxe5 Bxe5
{ At the end of the day, White can develop his Bishops faster, he has more control of the center, and the  Be5  may be attacked by f4.  White hasn't won any material, but he has a more comfortable position to play. }
