[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - The Pawn Fork Trick 4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Young Smithy - Heath, 2004  A chess friend shows me that just because I CAN execute the Pawn Fork Trick does not mean that I SHOULD execute the Pawn Fork Trick. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ So far, so good.  Both sides are developing naturally.  White is not worried about Black taking the e-pawn because time is everything, and the open e-file should be useful for White. }
5... b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ We can see that Black has played b5 with tempo, pushing the White Bishop away, and now develops with Bb7. }
7. Re1 Bc5
{ Up until now, both sides have followed all of the principles.  Now, though, Young Smithy thinks he sees a tactic! }
8. Nxe5
{ Time for another warning.  White is setting up the Pawn Fork Trick, but ... }
8... Nxe5 9. d4 Nfg4
{ The downside to the Pawn Fork Trick is that White has lost his best defender, and Black is ganging up rather dangerously on the Kingside, as all these arrows show. }
10. dxc5
{ 10.dxe5?  Bxf2+  is of course no good.   10.Re2!  preemptively defends against  f2  (, and I can win back my piece next move.  This was my only hope.) }
10... Qh4 { Black now threatens complete and utter disaster all over my King. }
11. h3 Qxf2+
{ Because this was against a friend, I played on a few more moves, but this game was over.  In my defence, this was a pretty subtle refutation of my play, but the point still stands: just because you CAN do a tactic doesn't mean you SHOULD.  Calculate!  Double-check your tactics! }
12. Kh1 Qg3
{ Black was merciless.  It's mate on  h2  unless I give up my Queen. } 13. hxg4
Nxg4 14. Qxg4 Qxg4 15. Rf1 Qxe4 { And now it's going to be mate on  g2  ! } 16.
Rxf7 Qxg2#
{ This was a pretty fantastic game from my opponent, and it shows how fast things can change.  I literally made 7 perfect moves, then one inaccuracy, then another ... and I was dead lost.  Chess is a cruel game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - POP QUIZ!"]
[Result "*"]

{ Gadimbayli - Paramzina, Baku 2016  In a surprising twist, Black's 85 pawn moves can't withstand White's onrushing army. }
1. e4 c5
{ This move fights for the center, but it often leaves Black behind in development.  She must always keep that in mind. }
2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This is considered the mainline of mainlines, but for our purposes, it is another pawn move that doesn't help development.  Black must be careful not to let White's pieces walk all over her. }
6. g3
{ This is a positional way of playing: White intends Bg2 and control of the long diagonal. }
6... b6
{ Black replies with the same idea, controlling the long diagonal, but this is too many pawn moves to get away with. }
7. Nd5
{ 'Smithy, doesn't this move a piece twice?'    Yes!  'Wouldn't Bg2 be better?'  100%.  This move, though, contains a drop of poison, and Black consumes it. }
7... Nfd7
{ Black responds by moving a piece twice ... backwards ... and hindering her development ... while moving nothing but pawns.   7...e6  makes far more sense, forcing White's Knight to move for a third time.  8.Nxf6  Qxf6  and though Black's Queen is developed early, it's not easy to attack her and development is currently equal. Compare that to the game. }
8. Bg5
{ More development, and now the e-pawn is pinned.  It's not easy to find a good move for Black here. }
8... h6
{ White has a massive lead in time.  Is there a way to take advantage?  Or does White have nothing better than to move her Bishop? }
9. Ne6
{ When looking at this position, because White is so far ahead in development, the first thought should be, 'Is there a tactic?'  The e-file isn't opened, so that doesn't work.  There are no sacrifices on  f7  , so that doesn't work.  Black did move a Kingside pawn, though, and we know that weakens the King's Diagonal.  Is it possible to force it open?   If you approach this position like that, you'll then find this brilliant move.  Black's Queen is trapped, and if she takes ... }
9... fxe6 { ... the King's Diagonal is wide open.  Now it becomes clear. } 10.
Qh5+ g6 11. Qxg6#
{ Sometimes the common tactics are easy to see.  Other times, like here, you need to do some digging.  When you have a lead in development, it's always good to start scanning for potential tactics.  Look for clues, like not being castled and pawn moves near her King.  There won't always be tactics, but sometimes there will be.  Here, those clues lead directly to the winning idea.  Game Source: 'Dodgy's Sicilian Tactics - 1000 Puzzles!' here on Chessable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - POP QUIZ!"]
[Result "*"]

{ cwtch  (2249)  - Grandhacker  (2402)  , Lichess 2019  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/EhtQiQcQ/black#12@@LinkEnd@@ }
1. f4 g6 2. b3 { Early on, both sides are fighting for the long diagonal. }
2... Bg7 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bb2 c5
{ This further controls the center, so it's not bad, but it's an unnecessary pawn move. }
5. e3 d4
{ Another pawn move.  Black gains space, but is that the purpose of the opening? }
6. Na4 b6
{ Black is rated 2400 in blitz.  He's seized space early on, but he hasn't developed yet.  Can he be punished?  Or Should White just focus on developing? }
7. Qf3
{ Black has made six pawn moves and has only one piece active.  We should thus look for tactics.  Of the most common motifs, there are no sacrifices on  f7  , the e-file is not open and Black's King's Diagonal is not weak.  He has moved his b-pawn, though, and that means his long diagonal is weak.  Can White take advantage?  Yes, with Qf3.  This should be your thought process.  Because you are bringing your Queen out early, you should also double-check that your Queen does not become trapped.   In the game, White missed this and played  7.Nf3?  , throwing away this opportunity, and he later lost the game. }
7... Qc7 8. Qxa8 Bb7 9. Qxa7
{ White's Queen is short on squares, but Black has no way of attacking her, and White can escape via pressure on  b6  or with a Bb5+.  Therefore, White is simply winning. }
