[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section II - Common Tactics"]
[Black "Tactical Section - POP QUIZ!"]
[Result "*"]

{ cwtch  (2249)  - Grandhacker  (2402)  , Lichess 2019  @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/EhtQiQcQ/black#13@@LinkEnd@@ }
1. f4 g6 2. b3 Bg7 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bb2 c5 5. e3 d4 6. Na4
{ In the previous example, Black blundered with b6 here.  Developing is, of course, better, but can White win a pawn? }
6... Nf6 7. Nxc5
{ White is rated 2250 and has just snatched a pawn.  Was this wise? } 7... dxe3
{ This move is obvious, because Black's d-pawn was hanging, but did you notice the tactical point behind it? }
8. dxe3 Qa5+
{ Of course we don't exchange Queens!  White has an undefended piece on the fifth rank, and Black has checks available.  Whenever you see this combination, your first thought should be, 'Does Qa5+ work?'  And it does. }
9. Qd2 Qxc5
{ Black wins a piece.  Both this and the previous example were taken from a blitz game between two very good players.  Black played a blunder with 6... b6 because  i  he overlooked the weakness on the long diagonal, and  ii  he didn't see the potential for Qa5+ indirectly defending his  c5  -pawn.  In other words, a very strong player missed the same tactics you're learning in this course... and so did his opponent!    It's blitz, so of course mistakes happen, but I saw these ideas instantly while watching the game.  Why?  Because I had spent the last three months preparing this material, and it jumped out like a clown in a scary movie.  The more you practice this material, the more the same will happen to you.  You are never too advanced to review these patterns. }
