[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Annotated Games - Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ This third and final section deals with annotated games.  It is designed to be the synthesis of what we've learned so far, of how the general opening principles can lead to utilizing various common tactical ideas.  When you finish studying these games, you should solidify everything we've reviewed so far, and hopefully the ideas start becoming natural before the end.  In particular, I am focusing on the MISTAKES of the losing side.  I want you to be able to see when your opponents make mistakes, because then you'll know how to capitalize.  That is how you should view these games: one side making a mistake  (either one big one or several small ones)  and the other side taking advantage.  This is an essential skill, and the example games tend to feature the same sorts of mistakes again and again.  My annotations focus on this area in depth.  For this reason, I have used many games from the past, featuring simuls, odds games, amateurs vs. masters and even some of my own games from my early days.  These games feature lots of mistakes, and so we have lots to learn.  Modern games feature very subtle errors, which is fine, but you need to learn how to spot  (and punish)  obvious mistakes before trying for the more subtle ones.  Every game is presented as an informational line, and the most critical moments are then 'trainable' with the Chessable interface. You are thus not memorizing these games, but only the key ideas.  Many of these games are quite beautiful, and I tried to make my annotations as fun as possible, so hopefully you enjoy learning from this section as much as I did making it. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 1:  Tarrasch - Kelz, Nuremberg 1890 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Tarrasch - Kelz, Nuremberg 1890   A perfect example of development being more important than material. }
1. e4
{ Also, don't worry, your screen isn't broken: White has no  a1  -Rook. White is Tarrasch, arguably the strongest player in the world in 1890; he offered Rook odds to make the game fair. You be the judge. }
1... e5 2. f4
{ Because White starts down a Rook, it makes sense to offer more material and try to attack. }
2... exf4 3. Nf3 g5
{ Black is already up a Rook. Why is he trying to defend his pawn ? He already has a winning advantage. He doesn't need to win more material. He just needs to finish development. Watch the rest of the game, as Black never finishes development. }
4. Bc4 g4 5. O-O gxf3 6. Qxf3
{ Black has spent five moves ... doing absolutely nothing. He has no pieces developed. True, he won a Knight, but he was already up a Rook. He didn't need any more material. Now White has a very strong initiative. }
6... Qf6 7. Nc3 Qd4+ { Oh look, Black is trying to win more material. } 8. Kh1
Qxc4 9. Qxf4
{ So the question now is, can Black get his King safe so his material advantage counts ? }
9... Ne7 10. Nd5
{ The Knight jumps in, threatening both Nf6+ and also blocking the Queen's protection of  f7  . }
10... Nxd5 { Black trades the Knight ... } 11. Qxf7+
{ ... but now  f7  falls, and Black is in severe danger. } 11... Kd8 12. d3
{ Getting tempo on the Queen while getting the Bishop into the game. } 12...
Qc6 13. Bg5+
{ White only has three pieces, but all of them are active and near the enemy King. Black has five  (!)  pieces not doing anything. That's decisive. }
13... Be7 { And now one final combination to finish it off. } 14. Qf8+ Rxf8 15.
Rxf8#
{ The Bishop is pinned, so that's mate ! You can have all the material in the world, but if they aren't doing anything, you might as well have nothing.   Time is everything. }
*

