1. d3
{ Your focus should be on finishing development and doing it with tempo if possible.  This both hits the Queen and prepares to bring the Bishop into the attack. }
1... Qc6 2. Bg5+ { Developing the final piece. } 2... Be7 3. Qf8+
{ With the King so in danger and Black completely undeveloped, you want to look for tactics.  This leads to mate in 2. }
3... Rxf8 4. Rxf8#
{ An example of developing with tempo and then cashing in with smart tactics.  Taken from the game Tarrasch - Kelz, 1890. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 2: NN - Tarrasch, Munich 1932 "]
[Result "*"]

{ NN - Tarrasch, Munich 1932   In 1932, Tarrasch was in his late 60s and far from his previous form from his glory days. You couldn't tell from this game, though. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { Both sides are developing normally. } 3... a6 4.
Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  Taking the Knight doesn't win the e-pawn.  dxc6  5.Nxe5  Qd4  This double-attack wins back the pawn, with a good game. }
4... Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 { Still with normal development. } 6. Nxe5
{ White sets up the pawn fork trick. } 6... Nxe4
{ Black ignores the Knight and jumps forward. He must be careful, though, because the e-file is open and he wasn't castled.   6...Nxe5  7.d4  is White's idea. }
7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. Qf3
{ 'White hits the Knight, but it makes more sense to use the open e-file, right ?' If you thought that, perfect, you are learning !   8.Re1 ?  Not like this, though.  Bxf2+  Oops.   8.Qe2  This is better; White doesn't win any material, but Black is under some pressure.  Qe7  9.Re1  Bf5  Black is hanging on, but he's on the defensive. }
8... Qh4
{ His King is in the center, but Black has lots of pieces near the White King. }
9. Nc3 Nxc3
{ Tarrasch starts a remarkable combination, offering a whole load of material, though it wasn't necessary, strictly speaking.   9...Ng5 !  winning a tempo on the Queen was stronger. }
10. Bxc6+ { White starts a combo, which wins material. } 10... bxc6 11. Qxc6+
Bd7 12. Qxa8+ { White grabs a Rook. } 12... Ke7 13. Qxh8
{ and now he grabs another one. Up two Rooks ! That's great ! But how many pieces does he have developed ? Zero ? Uh oh. }
13... Ne2+
{ The counter-attack: Black has four pieces staring at a bare King, with only pawns for cover. }
14. Kh1 Bxf2 15. h3
{ White tries to create some space, but now there's a pretty finale. } 15...
Qxh3+ 16. gxh3 Bc6+ 17. Kh2 Bg3#
{ We've seen this story many times: White grabbed a whole bunch of material, but in the process he fell behind in development. Black then had four pieces to attack with, and White's extra material no longer mattered. Time is everything.  Tarrasch's combination was actually faulty. Can you find the improvement that wins the game for White ? Without using a computer ? I couldn't. Let me know in the comments. Be honest ! No computer help ! }
*

