[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 3: Horowitz - NN, New York 1939 "]
[Result "*"]

{ Horowitz - NN, New York 1939   Black manages to castle, but he then moves his pieces away from his King. That leaves him defenceless when White's lead in development then comes knocking. }
1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. d4
{ White, a well-known master against an amateur, offers a pawn for speedy development. }
3... exd4 4. Nf3 Bb4+
{ Black develops with tempo and prepares to castle quickly. Excellent. } 5. c3
dxc3 6. O-O { White offers another pawn ! } 6... O-O
{ Wisely, Black castles instead of grabbing more material.   6...cxb2  7.Bxb2  Black is up two pawns, but time is everything. White has a very dangerous initiative. }
7. e5 { White uses his central pawn advantage. } 7... Ne4
{ In view of White's next move,   7...d5  should be considered, for example  8.exf6  dxc4  9.fxg7  Re8  10.Nxc3  Nc6  Where Black is ahead in development and can win the  g7  (-pawn and/or exchange Queens at anytime.) }
8. Bd5
{ White physically stops Black from playing d5, and Black's nice Knight is driven off. }
8... Nc5
{ Over the last two moves, White has pushed Black's best defender, his Knight, to the Queenside. Now his King is sitting bare. }
9. bxc3 { Hitting the Bishop... } 9... Ba5
{ ... and now the Bishop is also stuck on the Queenside. } 10. Ng5
{ Immediately White begins his attack. Both sides have two pieces developed, but there's still a difference in TIME. White has more pieces near the enemy King, so he has an advantage on that side of the board. Also, it's straightforward for White to develop his other forces, while it's tough for Black to bring his pieces into the defence. In other words, White has a very strong attack. }
10... Ne6
{ Bringing a piece back to defend, but that's a lot of moves with just this one Knight ... }
11. Qh5 { ... and White is bringing yet more flame into the fire. } 11... Nxg5
12. Bxg5
{ Trading pieces didn't help, because now Black has ZERO defenders, and White has three pieces hovering nearby  (plus the pawn)  . }
12... Qe8 13. Bf6
{ When you are attacking with so many pieces, tactics tend to appear. } 13...
h6
{ Desperation.   If Black takes the Bishop  13...gxf6  then  14.Be4  and now mate is unavoidable on  h7  (.) }
14. Qg6
{ And now it's mate on  g7  ! The Queen can't be taken because of the pin, the Bishop can't be taken because of the pin, and Black's army is asleep. An impressive attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 3.1: Horowitz - NN, New York 1939 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/5n2/8/1bB1P3/2p2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has a lead in development: what should be our focus? } 1. e5
{ White pushes his central pawn majority.  This does several things: 1  gains space, 2  forces the Knight to move, which gains more time, 3  takes a defender away from the King, and, 4  White can win more time against the Knight and Bishop soon.   1.Nxc3  Bxc3  2.bxc3  Nxe4  Now, I know I've said time is everything, but two pawns are also two pawns. The Knight will go back to the Kingside and Black doesn't have enough weaknesses for White to justify so much material. The mainline is similar but it prevents the Knight from returning to  f6  (and it doesn't lose a pawn.) }
1... Ne4 2. Bd5
{ A very important move!  This stops Black from playing d5, after which he would be fine, and also gains more time.   For instance,  2.Re1  d5!  Black returns the pawn to finish development and he has a fine game. In Horowitz-NN, New York 1939, White's attack was so successful precisely because Black could never finish development. }
