{ Can you find White's brilliant final combination? } 1. Bf6
{ This distracts the g-pawn, setting up a mating attack.  And it's beautiful as all get out!    1.Be4  g6  2.Qh6?  Qxe5  and White has nothing; this is why the g-pawn needs to be removed. }
1... gxf6
{ In Horowitz-NN, New York 1939, Black instead tried  1...h6  and resigned after  2.Qg6!  Let's see what happens if he takes the Bishop. }
2. Be4
{ 2.exf6?  Kh8!  and Black defends.  3.Be4?  doesn't work because of  3...Qxe4  , and the coming  Rg8  will defend against mate threats on  g7  (.  The key when looking at this position is recognizing the weakness of)  h7  (is more important than)  g7  (.) }
2... Qxe5 3. Qxh7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 4: McConnell - Morphy, New Orleans 1850"]
[Result "*"]

{ McConnell - Morphy, New Orleans 1850  White makes a lot of pawn moves against Morphy. Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. e4 e6
{ This is known as the French defence. Black temporarily allows White to build a big center... }
2. d4 d5 { ... and then immediately attacks it. } 3. e5
{ White gets a space advantage. } 3... c5
{ Black immediately counter-attacks. The question now becomes, 'Is White's pawn center a strength or an object for Black's attack?' }
4. c3 Nc6 5. f4
{ White is trying to secure his center, but that's five straight pawn moves, plus weakening his King's Diagonal. }
5... Qb6
{ This develops the Queen early, but White has no way of attacking her, and she pressures  d4  .  This is a thematic move in this pawn structure. }
6. Nf3 Bd7 7. a3 { Hmm, another pawn move... } 7... Nh6
{ Black has four pieces developed to White's one ... } 8. b4
{ ... and now ANOTHER pawn move ! That's seven out of the first eight moves ! Now, in a closed position like this, being behind in development doesn't matter so much. But if things open up, things can get bad very quickly. }
8... cxd4
{ That's why Black exchanges pawns here. The more the position opens, the greater his development advantage becomes. }
9. cxd4 Rc8
{ With the exchange of c-pawns, Black now places his Rook on the open c-file. }
10. Bb2 Nf5
{ Moving the Knight again, but it's now on a better square and adds more pressure to  d4  . All of Black's pieces are on their best squares. }
11. Qd3
{ White moves his Queen instead of getting ready to castle. Against Morphy. Uh oh. }
11... Bxb4+
{ A beautiful sacrifice. Black gets two pawns for the piece and completely opens the position, allowing his development to shine. White quickly crumbles. }
12. axb4 Nxb4 { The Knight threatens both the Queen and a fork on  c2  . } 13.
Qd2 Rc2 { Now the Rook invades. } 14. Qd1 Ne3
{ And now the Knight hops in, completing the trap of the Queen. Plus the Bishop on  b2  is hanging. And White's entire army is sleeping. A textbook example of using a sacrifice to open a blocked position to take advantage of a lead in development. }
*

