[Black "Game 4.1: McConnell - Morphy, New Orleans 1850"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1kb1r/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p3/3pPn2/1P1P1P2/P2Q1N2/1B4PP/RN2KB1R b KQk - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has made a lot of pawn moves, but the closed position makes it hard to take advantage.  Can Black open the position somehow? }
1... Bxb4+
{ Black gets two pawns for the piece and a strong attack against the uncoordinated and uncastled White position. Starting with  1...Nxb4?  doesn't really do anything:  2.axb4  Bxb4+  3.Nbd2  and White just develops normally; Black has no follow-up.  'Normal' development like Be7 is, of course, fine, but it doesn't use the most of Black's position. }
2. axb4 Nxb4 { The Knight comes in with tempo. } 3. Qd2 Rc2
{ Now the Rook slides in with tempo.  Nc2+ picking up the exchange is also winning. }
4. Qd1 Ne3
{ And the Queen is trapped.  Powerful play from McConnell-Morphy, New Orleans 1850 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 5: Macdonnell - NN, London 1830"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Macdonnell - NN, London 1830  White was one of the strongest players in the time pre-Morphy. Here he uncorks a beauty combination. Oh, and he's also playing without one Knight. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ This is known as the Evans Gambit  (or it would be if White had his Knight!)  . Since White is starting down material, it makes sense to sac pawns to open lines and attack. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ We can see the idea: first White lured the Bishop to  b4  , and now he will gain time to play c3 and d4 quickly. This is an extremely powerful way to play. }
5... Ba5 6. O-O Nf6 7. Qc2
{ This looks strange, but the Queen cannot be attacked, and she protects the  e4  -pawn. We will also see that this is a useful square for attacking later on. }
7... O-O 8. Ba3 { White finishes development and does it with tempo. } 8... Re8
{ Moves the Rook out of the way, but  f7  is a bit weaker now.   8...d6  Blocking the diagonal, reinforcing the center and preparing to develop the final Bishop is an excellent option. }
9. d4 { White is down a piece, so he needs to open lines to try to attack. }
9... d5
{ Conversely, Black should try to keep things calm and not open any lines... so the opposite of this move!  This is exactly what White wants. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. dxe5 Nxc3
{ Black gets greedy and pinches a pawn. What's more important, material or time ? }
12. Rad1 { Brings his Rook in with tempo ! } 12... Nxd1 13. Rxd1
{ White is fully developed; Black's Kingside has no defenders and his Queenside is sleeping. }
13... Bd7
{ White is fully developed, so he should look for a way to cash in. What's a thematic approach to do that ? }
14. Bxf7+ Kxf7
{ The King is weak, but what is the follow-up ? Ng5 would be perfect, but the Queen covers that square... }
15. Rxd7+ { Pulling the Queen away from the defense of the  g5  -square ! }
15... Qxd7 16. Ng5+ Kg8 17. Qxh7#
{ Once more, we see the few White forces coordinating and taking down the greater but dormant Black army. While the tactics are nice, please pay attention to the common error: Black is up material and he tries to win more before finishing development. That is the seed of many defeats. }
*

