[Black "Game 6: NN - Vargha, Budapest 1918"]
[Result "*"]

{ NN - Vargha, Budapest 1918  White takes action in the center without first castling. Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5
{ This is known as the Tarrasch defence. Black tends to get a worse pawn structure but gains active pieces. }
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 { Both sides develop naturally so far. } 6. g3
{ White now intends to put his Bishop on the long diagonal, where it will aim at the potentially weak  d5  -pawn. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg2 cxd4
{ Black trades on  d4  , which clarifies the situation in the center. } 8. Nxd4
{ White gets a lovely Knight, though. } 8... Qb6
{ 'Doesn't this bring the Queen out early ?' Yes. 'Wouldn't a developing move like Bc5 be better ?' Yes. If you're thinking like that, you're learning ! }
9. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Black's pawns may look strong, but they will be targets in the middlegame. White will finish development and then either pressure on the c-file and/or push e4 to open the center and let his Bishop live. }
10. e4
{ Uh oh. White starts opening the center BEFORE finishing his development. He wants to prove that Black's pawns are weak, but the opening isn't about weak pawns, it's about finishing development ! }
10... Bb4
{ Bringing a piece out, pressuring the center and preparing to castle.   10...Ba6 !  first was even better. }
11. Bd2 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4
{ The center is wide open. Development is about equal. Position looks balanced. }
13... Ba6
{ Except White can't castle. His King is now stuck on the open e-file. } 14.
Rc1 O-O { Black brings his King to safety. } 15. Rxc6
{ White, not knowing what else to do, wins a pawn. Winning pawns is the point of the opening, right ? }
15... Qxc6
{ A pretty move, clearing the e-file and deciding the game instantly. } 16.
Bxc6 Rfe8+ { White wins the Rook as well, but ... } 17. Bxe8 Rxe8+
{ 17...Rxe8+  18.Qe2  Rxe2+  and Black picks up the Bishop as well next move. }
*

