[SetUp "1"]

{ How to take advantage of White's King position? } 1... Qxc6
{ Clearing the e-file in style! } 2. Bxc6 Rfe8+ 3. Bxe8 Rxe8+
{ White is now forced to give up material. } 4. Qe2 Rxe2+ 5. Kf1 Rxd2+
{ Black is several pieces ahead.  From NN-Vargha, Budapest 1918 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 7: Nimzovich - Alapin, Riga 1913"]
[Result "*"]

{ Nimzovich - Alapin, Riga 1913  Black decides to go pawn grabbing while only developing his Queen. Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. e4 e6
{ This is the French defence: Black gets a solid set-up, but it can be hard to develop his light-square Bishop. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 { So far, both sides are developing pretty normally. } 4.
exd5
{ White clarifies the center. This is a perfectly fine way to play  (and the way I recommend in the Practical Tips Section)  , but note that it allows Black's bad Bishop to come into the game. }
4... Nxd5
{ Or, it should have brought the bad Bishop into the game, but Black decides to move his Knight twice instead.   4...exd5  This is of course the better move. Many French players don't like playing this structure because it is 'boring'. Maybe so, but don't let boredom make you play inferior moves ! }
5. Nf3 c5 { And now an unnecessary pawn move ! } 6. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ It's not easy to attack Black's Queen here, but you must always be careful when your Queen is developed early. }
7. Be3 { White develops while defending his pawn. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 a6
{ That's a second non-developing pawn move for Black. He must proceed with caution. }
9. Be2
{ Black faces a tough choice. If he does nothing, White will play Bf3, bringing his Bishop to a beautiful diagonal and hitting his Queen... }
9... Qxg2
{ ... or he could go back grabbing with his only developed piece. Oh dear. }
10. Bf3 { The Bishop comes here anyway. } 10... Qg6 11. Qd2
{ White now prepares to castle Queenside, completing his development. Such a commanding lead in time is easily worth a pawn. }
11... e5
{ A third non-developing pawn move, after moving his Queen around grabbing pawns ! Black cannot get away with this. }
12. O-O-O
{ Time is everything ! White completes his development, even at the cost of his Knight. }
12... exd4 13. Bxd4
{ Sure, Black won a piece, good for him, but now the e-file is completely open. }
13... Nc6
{ Black tries to develop, but it's too late. Now starts one of the prettiest combinations in chess. }
14. Bf6
{ An empty-square sacrifice ! White clears the d-file, and now all the major pieces aim at the bare King.   14.Rhe1+  This is natural, but after  Be6  it isn't clear how to break through. }
14... Qxf6 15. Rhe1+ Be7
{ Now if   15...Be6  then  16.Qd7#  is mate, because the Bishop is pinned ! THIS is why we needed to play Bf6 first, so the invasion on the d-file could occur. }
16. Bxc6+ { This removes a defender of the  d8  -square. } 16... Kf8
{ 16...bxc6  17.Qd8# } 17. Qd8+ Bxd8 18. Re8#
{ Each of Black's non-developing pawn moves made sense, and none were fatal by themselves; taken together, though, they became a considerable loss in time, and White capitalized beautifully.   Do you want to play games like this ?   Then focus on developing as fast as possible !   Don't make unnecessary pawn moves !   Don't go pawn grabbing !   Time is everything ! }
*

