[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 7.2: Nimzovich - Alapin, Riga 1913"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/1p3ppp/p1n3q1/8/3B4/5B2/PPPQ1P1P/2KR3R w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has a massive lead in development, but how to cash in? } 1. Bf6
{ Clearing the d-file is the first necessary step.   1.Rhe1+  doesn't actually do much after  1...Be6  , as there is no immediate follow-up.   1.Bxc6!?  first is a good try, but it gives Black a chance to play  Qxc6  , which reinforces the d7-square. White is still dominating, but it's not mate.   Finally,  1.Bxg7!?  would also be possible, as it also clears the d-file.  Bf6  (is better, though, because it controls the key)  e7  (and)  d8  (squares directly near the King.  It's complicated, but the main point is this: clear the d-file before bringing your last Rook into the game.  Do that and you win!) }
1... Qxf6 2. Rhe1+ Be7
{ If  2...Be6  3.Qd7#  is mate! This is why we need to clear the d-file first, to allow  Qd7  to come immediately. }
3. Bxc6+ { Removing the defender of  d8  . } 3... bxc6
{ In the actual game Black delayed mate by playing Kf8, but that only adds a move to the solution. }
4. Qd8# { And that's mate, as in Nimzovich-Alapin, Riga 1913 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 8: Duras - Simek, Pisek 1912"]
[Result "*"]

{ Oldrich Duras - Simek, Pisek 1912  Oldrich Duras was one of the strongest tournament players of his era. This game was part of a 31 board simultaneous exhibition. In other words, he's playing 31 games at the same time. This explains why he doesn't play the best moves at the critical moment, but he still blows his amateur opponent off the board in under 20 moves. }
1. d4 d5 2. e4
{ White offers a pawn on move 2. Most masters consider this dubious, but Duras makes it look unbeatable here. }
2... dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3
{ For the pawn, White has two open files and easy development. Because of the open f-file, Black needs to watch for tricks on  f7  in particular. }
5... e6 6. Bd3 Bb4
{ Not bad, but the Bishop probably wants to be on  e7  . It can be a target here. }
7. O-O Bxc3
{ Black then exchanges his Bishop unprovoked. Black, an amateur facing the mighty Duras, likely thought exchanging pieces would help him survive longer. He was wrong. }
8. bxc3 O-O 9. Ba3
{ Thanks to that exchange, White can bring his Bishop to this diagonal with tempo. }
9... Re8 10. Ne5
{ It's only move 10, but White is near fully developed and has enormous pressure on  f7  and the Kingside in general. Black only has two pieces developed, and his  e8  -Rook would probably rather be on  f8  anyway. The gambit has worked beautifully so far. }
10... Nc6
{ In fact, White's pressure is so great that this developing move simply loses. }
11. Nxf7 { White crashes in on the thematic  f7  -square. } 11... Qd5
{ Black tries to hang on.  Taking the Knight is suicide.   11...Kxf7  12.Qh5+ !  The Knight is pinned, and Black gets swept away.  Kg8  13.Rxf6  and if  Qxf6  14.Qxe8+  Qf8  15.Qxf8# }
12. Nh6+ { Another shot ! } 12... Kh8
{ 12...gxh6  13.Rxf6  White regains his piece while shattering the Kingside; the end is near. }
13. Qd2
{ This gives Black a chance. If this weren't a simul, Duras surely would have found the immediately winning combo instead:   13.Rxf6 !!  gxf6  14.Qg4  The Rook is ready to slide over, White is attacking with everything, Black is defending with nothing, the game is over. The immediate threat is Nf7#. }
13... Ne7 14. Nf7+ Kg8 15. Rxf6 { Now Duras finds the right idea. } 15... gxf6
16. Qh6 f5 17. Ng5
{ Black resigned, as mate is coming after White cashes in on  h7  . Black really made one fundamental mistake in this game: exchanging his Bishop on  c3  unprovoked. White's initiative then snowballed out of control. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 8.1: Duras - Simek, Pisek 1912"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/3P4/2N2p2/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Finish development as quickly as possible from here. } 1. Nxf3
{ Obviously we take the pawn, but it's important to take it with the Knight.  1.Qxf3?!  Qxd4  2.Be3  Qg4!  and White has a small lead in development, but not worth two pawns. }
1... e6 2. Bd3
{ Because the pawn is on  e6  , Bc4 makes less sense: it's just staring at Black's wall of pawns on that diagonal.  On  d3  instead, the Bishop aims at the eventual Black Kingside on a completely open diagonal. }
2... Bb4 3. O-O
{ Castling not only gets the King safe, but it puts the Rook on the open f-file.  This is also why we probably don't want to play Bf4, because then the Bishop would get in the way of the Rook. }
3... Bxc3 4. bxc3 O-O 5. Ba3
{ Ba3 completes our development with tempo, though Bg5  (an annoying pin)  , Rb1  (using the newly open file)  and Ne5  (improving the Knight opening the f-file)  are all good alternatives.  As mentioned, Bf4 is not ideal, because the Bishop gets in the way of our Rook on the f-file.  It's the wrong idea.  We do not want to hinder our development.  After Ba3, White has an excellent attacking position.  From Duras-Simek, Pisek 1912. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 8.2: Duras - Simek, Pisek 1912"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/4N3/3P4/B1PB4/P1P3PP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is near fully developed.  How to continue? } 1. Nxf7
{ The bigger your lead in development, the more you should look for tactics.  Here  f7  is especially weak, with only the King defending it and our Rook on the f-file staring down at it, so this should be the first move we look at.   1.Nxc6?!  bxc6  means our Knight that has moved three times gets exchanged for Black's Knight that has moved once. Yes, it ruins the pawn structure, but it takes away a potential attacker and is not in the spirit of this position. }
1... Kxf7
{ In the game Duras-Simek, Pisek 1912 Black did not take the Knight.  What would be the refutation if he did? }
2. Qh5+
{ The Knight is pinned, so the Queen is immune and now stands on a dangerous square.  Also, don't forget about the Bishop on  a3  , which cuts off the important dark squares. }
2... Kg8 { 2...g6  3.Qxh7#  is nice and simple } 3. Rxf6
{ Crushing!  Removing the final defender and exposing both  h7  and  e8  . }
3... Qxf6 4. Qxe8+
{ Taking on  h7  with either piece also works, but don't overlook free Rooks! }
4... Qf8 5. Qxf8#
{ White's attack worked so well because he had far more attackers than Black's defenders.  White was able to sacrifice both his Rook and Knight and STILL overwhelm the Black forces.  That's the power of development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 9: NN - Bird, England 1850"]
[Result "*"]

{ NN - Bird, England 1850  White spends his first 8 moves trying to win a Rook while Black's army surrounds his King. Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ At the time, this was a new opening and people weren't sure how best to respond. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ This ... is probably not the best response. Bringing your Queen out early is rarely good. }
5. Nb5
{ White tries to take advantage by targeting  c7  , but that's the third time this Knight has moved. }
5... Bc5 { Black develops with tempo, threatening mate ! } 6. Qf3
{ 6.Nxc7+ ?  Kd8  and White has no time to take the Rook because of the mate threat, so he just loses the Knight. }
6... Nf6
{ Black ignores the threat and keeps developing ! We know development is important, but is it worth a Rook ? }
7. Nxc7+ Kd8 8. Nxa8 Re8
{ Bringing the Rook to the e-file with tempo. Black is nearly fully developed, White has only his Queen. He needs to be very careful.   8...Nxe4 !  immediately is even better. }
9. Bd3 Nxe4 10. O-O { White castles, but not into safety. } 10... Nxf2
{ The classic weakness on  f7  ... or in this case,  f2  . } 11. Rxf2
{ 11.g3  allows a pretty mate as well.  Ng4+  12.Rf2  Re1+  13.Bf1  Qxh2# }
11... Re1+ 12. Bf1 Nd4
{ Bringing yet another piece in, and White gets swept away. } 13. Qxf7 Ne2+
{ The Knight is attacked by both the Rook and Bishop, but neither can take it because both are pinned. }
14. Kh1 Rxf1+ 15. Rxf1 Ng3#
{ Yet another final position where one side has lots of material but no development ... and the other side is delivering mate.   Time is everything. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 9.1: NN - Bird, England 1850"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "N1bkr3/pp1p1ppp/2n2n2/2b5/4P2q/3B1Q2/PPP2PPP/RNB1K2R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has won the Rook in the corner, but he is dangerously behind in development.  How should Black continue? }
1... Nxe4
{ Opening the e-file for our Rook.   The most common error is  1...Nd4?  This allows White to play  2.Qf4!  , which will trade Queens and/or invade on  c7.  Opening the e-file is more important. }
2. O-O
{ In the game, White simply castled, trying to get his King to safety.   2.Bxe4  is the most accurate move, because it forces Black to play  2...Nd4!  first, gaining a tempo on the Queen and also threatening  c2  with a fork. The Bishop is pinned and Black can win it next move. Play might continue  3.Qg3  Qxe4  4.Be3  Nxc2  5.Kd2  Bxe3+  6.fxe3  Nxa1.  It's a very messy position, and both Kings are open, but Black has regained some material and has a fighting chance. }
2... Nxf2
{ The weakness on  f2  !  This both exposes White's King and also fully opens the e-file for the Rook to join the attack.   2...Bxf2+  is less accurate, but for a pretty subtle point.  3.Rxf2  Nxf2  4.Bf1!  Now White threatens to take the Knight without allowing a Rook intermezzo on the back rank. Now if  4...Ng4  5.Qf4!  Re4  6.Qg5+!  Qxg5  7.Bxg5+  White has exchanged Queens and the danger has passed. This is a subtle line, but the main takeaway is hopefully an intuitive one: it's better to take on  f2  (with the Knight first because it sets up a pin and immediately allows the Rook into the game.) }
3. Rxf2 Re1+
{ White is in grave danger: his Rook is pinned, so Black can take it at any point, but he also faces a very tough defence, which he was unable to hold in NN-Bird, England 1850. }
*

