{ White's King looks vulnerable.  Is there a way to take advantage? } 1... Ne2+
{ Both the Bishop and Rook are pinned to the King, so the Knight is immune. }
2. Kh1 Rxf1+
{ Coercing the Rook off of  f2  (, which will open our Bishop's control of)  g1   .  2...Ng3+  3.Kg1  Rxf1#  is the same idea but in reverse. }
3. Rxf1 Ng3# { A pretty finale in NN-Bird, England 1850. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 10: Young Smithy - SanB, Internet 2004"]
[Result "*"]

{ Young Smithy - SanB, Internet 2004  Want proof that the principles work ? Here's one of my favourite games, played in Morphy style. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 { Young Smithy really liked the King's Gambit. } 2... d6
{ Notice how Black seems confused in this game. First, he defends his pawn, which is fine... }
3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bc4 exf4
{ ... but then he takes it a few moves later, and now his Bishop is stuck behind the  d6  -pawn. Meanwhile, White plays nothing but natural moves. }
5. d4 Bg4
{ Whenever Black plays this was Bxf7+ possible, we should see if there is a tactic. }
6. Bxf4
{ 6.Bxf7+ ?  This tempting idea doesn't work.  Kxf7  7.Ng5+   7.Ne5+  Nxe5  8.dxe5  Bxd1  7...Qxg5  Even though it doesn't work, it's worth spending time calculating. If something changes, maybe it will work then, and we'll be ready. }
6... Be7 7. O-O
{ I've castled, I control the center, so I just need to develop my Queenside and things will be perfect. }
7... h6 { Black makes an unnecessary pawn move... } 8. Nc3 g5
{ ... and then goes insane and makes this one ! He's trying to attack me, but as we know, the opening is not about attacking, it's about finishing development ! }
9. Bg3 Bh5
{ This is too much: moving a piece again, with his King stuck in the middle and with me fully developed ? I need to open the position to take advantage. }
10. e5 { The flood gates open. } 10... dxe5 11. d5
{ The best move. I want to take on  e5  with a piece, opening the e-file completely.  Instead:   11.dxe5  is weaker  Qxd1  12.Raxd1  Exchanging Queens isn't the end of the world, but it's harder to mate him. }
11... Nd4 12. Bxe5 { The double attack forces him to lose more time. } 12...
Nxf3+ 13. Rxf3 { Having first offered a pawn, I now offer the exchange ! }
13... Bxf3
{ 13...Nf6  Had Black declined, I had planned  14.Qf1  Though the computer says   14.d6  is an immediate win. I have to be honest, though: Young Smithy did not see that !  14...Bxf3  15.Qxf3  with a similar position, but where Black, with an extra tempo of development, has hopes of surviving. }
14. Qxf3
{ Doesn't this look like a Morphy game ? I have a million pieces developed, my opponent defends with one. }
14... Bc5+
{ Coming with tempo, but this is a mixed blessing, as this opens the e-file to his King. }
15. Kh1 f6 { Many moves win here, but I play the beautiful ... } 16. Re1
{ ... offering another piece to bring my Rook into the attack.  As the glut of arrows show, White's attack is irresistible. }
16... fxe5 17. Rxe5+ { The end is now imminent. } 17... Be7 18. Bb5+
{ Opening even more lines. } 18... c6 19. dxc6 Nf6 20. Qxf6
{ He can't take because of the pin ! } 20... a6 21. c7+
{ Perhaps my most beautiful game; certainly my most Romantic one. See ? If I can play like this using opening principles, so can you ! It really works ! }
*

