[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 10.1: Young Smithy - SanB, Internet 2004"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/4p3/4PP2/5N2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How should White continue development? } 1. Bc4
{ Thematic and powerful.  1.Nc3  and  1.d4  are equally good.  1.Bb5  is acceptable, but with the f-file likely opening up, it makes more sense for the Bishop to aim at the  f7  (-square.) }
1... exf4 2. d4
{ Black abandons the center, so we should take it immediately. } 2... Bg4 3.
Bxf4
{ Winning back the pawn while also developing a piece.  No other move should cross your mind here.   Something like  3.O-O  allows Black to justify his play with  3...Qf6  , preparing to castle Queenside while hanging onto his extra pawn. Notice how much harder it is to develop our dark-square Bishop here. }
3... Be7 4. O-O
{ Castling puts the Rook on the newly open f-file while also getting the King safe. }
4... h6 5. Nc3
{ White has finished development with a beautiful position.  From Young Smithy - SanB, Internet 2004 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 11: Young Smithy - Tex, Internet 2004"]
[Result "*"]

{ Young Smithy - 'tex', Internet 2003  A shockingly accurate game from young me, though really I just follow the base principles, find one tactic and I beat someone rated nearly 1800. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3
{ White's Bishop has moved three times, but the argument is that Black's pawns are a weakness. }
5... h6
{ Black was worried about Ng5, attacking  f7  , but this is an unnecessary pawn move. }
6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1 Bc5 8. h3
{ 'Smithy, isn't this an unnecessary pawn move as well ?' Yes ! Young Smithy did not have the advantage of studying this course yet !  (I was worried about Black attacking)  f2   , but I could have played like in the game:  8.c3  Ng4 ?!  9.d4  and the attack is repelled. }
8... d6 9. c3 g5
{ Black wanted to attack me with a pawn storm, but as we know, the opening isn't about attacking, it's about finishing development ! This just creates weaknesses. }
10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 { I now own the center. } 11... Bb4 12. Nc3
{ And I've nearly finished development. } 12... O-O
{ Black, seeing how the center is about to open, castles, but this shows how silly his ninth move was.   12...g4  What would happen if Black tried to keep attacking with his pawns ?  13.e5 !  I would attack in the center !  gxf3  14.exf6+  Be6   14...Kf8  15.Qxf3  and Black is struggling to survive.  15.d5  and Black collapses. This makes sense, because Black is attacking my castled King with pawns while I'm attacking his uncastled King with everything. }
13. Qd3
{ I bring my Queen out, prepare an eventual Rad1 ... and plan a sneaky tactic. }
13... Ba5 { Black moves this piece for a second time... } 14. e5 Nb4
{ ... so he could then move this piece a second time ! See, Black saw my Queen and he thought of how he could attack it ... but that cost him two tempi to move his already developed pieces to worse squares than where they started. Even worse, it allows my sneaky tactic. }
15. Qg6+
{ The  f7  -pawn is pinned, so the Queen is immune. The weaknesses created after g5 are now decisive. }
15... Kh8 16. Qxh6+ Nh7 17. Bxg5 { Developing with tempo ! } 17... f6
{ Black's position was terrible, but now it's mate in four. } 18. Bxf6+ Rxf6
19. exf6 Qxf6 20. Re8+ Qf8 21. Rxf8#
{ A nice game where I followed the opening principles almost perfectly  (that one unnecessary pawn move though...)  and then capitalized with one well-timed tactic. About as clean as Young Smithy got, all thanks to opening principles ! }
*

