[Black "Game 12: Young Smithy - sompon, Internet 2004"]
[Result "*"]

{ Young Smithy - 'sompon', Internet 2004  The final example of Young Smithy using opening principles. }
1. e4 e6
{ This is the French defence, an opening I've never liked playing against. } 2.
d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. c4
{ This has always been my favourite way of playing this position, as it generally leads to more open positions. }
4... c6
{ This is a thematic move, but it's a non-developing pawn move, so Black needs to be careful. }
5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd3 Qe7+
{ Black is hoping either to exchange Queen or to misplace my Knight on  e2  . }
7. Ne2
{ The thing is, the Knight on  e2  is still developed and lets White castle, whereas the Queen on  e7  is developed early and may be a target. }
7... Nf6 8. O-O Be6
{ Black blocks the e-file and threatens to win the  c4  -pawn. } 9. Nf4
{ This moves a piece twice, but it unblocks the e-file and prepares to exchange on e6. If Black moves his Bishop, then he's wasting more time; if he doesn't, then he gets weaknesses near his King. }
9... dxc4 10. Nxe6 fxe6
{ 10...cxd3 ?  11.Nxg7+  is clearly not what Black wants. } 11. Bxc4
{ We can see the problem: the  e6  -pawn is weak, and White's Bishop and Rooks will soon target it. Also, Black still hasn't castled... }
11... Bxc3 { Black, perhaps feeling the pressure, starts exchanging pieces... }
12. bxc3 b5
{ And now he makes an unnecessary pawn move ! Given my lead in development, I immediately look for tactics. }
13. Bxe6 { And I find some ! The Bishop is immune because of the open e-file. }
13... Na6
{ 13...Qxe6  14.Re1  Hopefully this is familar from the tactical section. } 14.
Re1
{ I occupy the e-file anyway, and Black is in huge trouble. He can't castle through check, so he tries to manually hop his King away. }
14... Kf8 15. Bb3 { Opening the e-file for the Rook. } 15... Qd6 16. Re6
{ Coming in with tempo. } 16... Qc7 17. Ba3+
{ Developing my last piece with tempo ! } 17... c5 18. dxc5
{ 18.Qf3 !  This immediately, hitting the Rook in the corner, was even better. }
18... Nxc5 19. Qf3
{ The Queen joins the attack, whereas Black is playing without either Rook  (and both his minor pieces are pinned as well !) }
19... Re8 { This allows a pretty finish. } 20. Rxf6+ gxf6 21. Qxf6+ Qf7 22.
Qxf7#
{ My opponent wasted time in the opening. I took advantage through the open e-file, and then I just kept developing with tempo until my initiative was unstoppable. }
*

