{ From Young Smithy-sompon, Internet 2004, what is the fastest way to win? } 1.
Rxf6+
{ This clears the defences and wins immediately, though admittedly virtually every other logical move also wins.  I've added every logical move I could think of as a soft-fail, so it will take some serious effort to fail this one. }
1... gxf6 2. Qxf6+ Qf7 3. Qxf7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 13: Horvath - Mayer, Budapest 1917"]
[Result "*"]

{ Horvath - Mayer, Budapest 1917  White shows us a masterclass in development with tempo and playing with the initiative. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to gain a lead in time. } 4... Bxb4
5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O Nf6 7. d4
{ For the pawn, White has castled and has a firm grip on the center. That said, Black has three pieces developed, so if he doesn't waste any time he should be okay. }
7... Nxe4
{ The purpose of the opening is not to win pawns ! Black must now be very careful. }
8. Re1 { White prepares to occupy the e-file. } 8... Nd6
{ Black gets off the e-file, attacks the Bishop, protects  f7  ... but this was not careful enough. Notice how this Knight has moved three times in the opening, violating the principles, and White can punish it.   8...d5 !  Black stays in the game with this, both developing with tempo and also fighting for the center. }
9. Bg5
{ White ignores Black's threat and creates his own ! From this point forward, every White move comes with tempo, and White gives us a master class in attacking play. }
9... Ne7
{ 9...f6  This is the other move to save the Queen, but now White can win by opening the e-file.  10.dxe5 !  fxg5   10...Nxc4  11.exf6+  Discovered check.  Kf8  12.fxg7+  Discovered attack.  Kxg7  13.Bxd8  11.exd6+  The e-file is now Black's demise. White is completely winning, and best play is  Kf8  12.Qd5 !  Qf6  13.Nxg5 !  with the threat of Nxh7+ Rxh7 and Qg8#. }
10. Nxe5 { The Knight joins the attack on  f7  and fully opens the e-file. }
10... f6
{ Let's see what happens if Black tried to eliminate the other annoying Bishop.   10...Nxc4  11.Bxe7 !  Drawing the Queen to the e-file.  Qxe7  12.Nxc4  Wins the Queen.  Castling would save the King but drop loads of material.   10...O-O  11.Nxf7  Rxf7  12.Bxe7  The Rook can't recapture because of the pin, and  Qe8  13.Bxd6  Qd8  is easily winning, such as  14.Bxf7+  Kxf7  15.Qh5+  leads to mate. }
11. Bxf6
{ The Bishop sacrifices itself to completely expose the King's Diagonal. }
11... gxf6
{ If Black tries to take the other Bishop   11...Nxc4  then the game finishes in a similar way to the game.  12.Qh5+  g6  13.Nxg6  White's threats include winning the Rook in the corner, winning the Knight on  e7  (and a deadly discovered check with the Queen.) }
12. Qh5+ Kf8 13. Qh6+ { The Queen is closing in for the kill. } 13... Ke8 14.
Ng6
{ The Knight is immune because of the pins, and now the Rook will be gobbled up.   14.Qxf6  The computers tell us that this is a faster forced mate, for the record. }
14... Nf5
{ Black defends against the coming Qg7.   14...Nxc4  Taking the Bishop still doesn't help.  15.Qg7  Not only is the Rook trapped, but  hxg6  16.Qxh8+  Kf7  17.Qxd8  Black loses the Queen as well. }
15. Qh5 { The Queen sets up an epic discovered check on the King's Diagonal. }
15... Ng7
{ White now combines the weakness on  f7  , the King's Diagonal and the open e-file for a beautiful finale. }
16. Bf7+ Kxf7 17. Ne5+ Ke6 18. Nf7#
{ What a finish ! Literally half of this game was White developing and attacking with tempo. Black made one mistake, but because he was down in time, that was enough to sweep him away. }
*

