{ The brilliant conclusion of Horvath-Mayer, Budapest 1917. } 1. Bf7+
{ Drawing the King to  f7  , which sets up a devastating double-check.    1.Nxh8+?  doesn't work because it's only a single check. Black has time to take the Queen, and though  1...Nxh5  2.Nf7  traps the Black Queen,  2...d5!  3.Nxd8  dxc4  leaves White down too much material. }
1... Kxf7 2. Ne5+ Ke6 3. Nf7#
{ A novel mating pattern, set-up by the fantastic Bf7+!! sacrifice. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 14: Capablanca - Friedman, Karlsbad 1933"]
[Result "*"]

{ Capablanca - Friedman, Karlsbad 1933  Black starts attacking without finishing his development against one of the most dominant World Champions in history. Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
{ In terms of development, this may be seen as an unnecessary pawn move. In terms of controlling the center, though, this helps White secure important central territory. As such, it is a fine move. }
2... e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Nf3
{ So far, both sides have followed the principles, developing with virtually every move. }
6... c6
{ This is an old-fashioned, passive way of playing. Black simply reinforces his center. Compared to White's c4, this is less useful. }
7. Rc1 dxc4
{ This is a waste of time. If Black wants to take on  c4  , he should wait until White moves his Bishop.   7...O-O  For instance, if Black castles, we can reach the exact same position  8.Bd3  dxc4  9.Bxc4  but where Black has already castled, a gain of tempo. }
8. Bxc4 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7
{ We can see Black's idea: he played b5 with tempo, and now he can develop his Bishop to  b7  . He needs one more move to play  c5  , though, for this Bishop to be actually active. }
10. a4
{ 'Smithy, isn't this an unnecessary pawn move ?' Yes. This move is thematic in similar positions, but White should finish his development and castle first. }
10... b4 11. Bxf6
{ White wants to play Ne4, but he needs to exchange on f6 first.   11.Ne4  if White tries to play this first, then  Nxe4  12.Bxe7  Nxf2! !  13.Bxd8  Nxd1  and Black is up a pawn. }
11... Nxf6 12. Ne4 Nd7
{ Black moves his Knight again without finishing development. } 13. O-O f5
{ And now Black goes crazy ! He wants to attack and push the Knight out of the center, but the opening isn't about attacking. Time is everything. }
14. Ng3 h5
{ Black is committed to his attack at least, but again, this is the wrong idea. }
15. Qb3
{ White develops his last piece and hits the weak  e6  -pawn. His plan should be how to take take advantage of Black's King in the center. }
15... Rh6 { Black is forced to defend with this strange move. } 16. Bxf5
{ White is fully developed, so he sacrifices to open the position.  Playing simply with   16.Bc4  was also good. }
16... exf5 17. Nxf5
{ White has two pawns for the piece, but more importantly, Black's King is open and White is ready to jump in. Also notice how the Knight gains a tempo on the Rook. }
17... Rg6 18. Qg8+ Bf8 19. N3h4
{ Now the other Knight hits the Rook. This is why we don't develop the major pieces early, because they can get pushed around. }
19... Rf6
{ White's pieces now coordinate beautifully to deliver the coup de grace. } 20.
Nxg7+ Ke7 21. Nhf5+ Rxf5 22. Qe6#
{ Black tried to attack too early, and it was his own King that became the target. }
