[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 15: Martin Bier - Salomon Ricardo-Rocamora, Hamburg 1876"]
[Result "*"]

{ Martin Bier - Salomon Ricardo-Rocamora, Hamburg 1876  White focuses on development; Black focuses on winning material.  Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Bc4 cxb2 5. Bxb2
{ White is down two pawns, but he has lots of open lines and rapid development. Black's best bet is to return one or both pawns to catch up on development. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Nf3 Bb4
{ So far, Black is focusing on catching up on development. Good. } 8. Qc2 d6 9.
O-O-O
{ Of the two possibilities, this is clearly the more dangerous side to castle.   9.O-O  is simple and offers good compensation. }
9... Bxc3
{ Unprovoked exchanges, especially Bishop for Knight, are rarely good ideas, especially in such open positions. }
10. Bxc3 O-O 11. e5
{ White is near fully developed, whereas Black's Queenside is inactive. White needs to open the position and use his development before Black catches up. }
11... Ne8 12. h4
{ When up in time, push pawns and open lines. Here White prepares Ng5 and bringing the Knight into the attack. }
12... Qe7 13. Ng5
{ White threatens mate, forcing Black to defend. As long as Black is defending, he can't finish development  (or use his extra material)  . }
13... g6 14. exd6 { Opening more lines. } 14... Nxd6
{ This natural move moves a piece a little further away from the Kingside and is the decisive mistake.   14...cxd6  This is ugly but necessary. When you grab pawns instead of developing, you are often forced to make ugly moves to survive. }
15. Rhe1 { Finishing development with tempo. } 15... Qd8 16. Qb2
{ White prepares a mating starting with Bh8. } 16... Nxc4 17. Rxd8 Nxb2
{ Black thinks he's fine after exchanging Queens, but White's active pieces allow a final combination. }
18. Rxf8+ Kxf8 19. Nxh7+ Kg8 20. Re8+ Kxh7 21. Rh8#
{ Notice that Black never managed to develop his Queenside. White never gave him a chance. Once you have a lead in development, you want to keep creating threats and never let your opponent back into the game. }
*

