[SetUp "1"]

{ The finale of Bier-Ricardo-Rocamora, Hamburg 1876.  Black has won a piece and thinks an exchange of Queens will save him.  What should White do? }
1. Rxd8 { White jumps right in! } 1... Nxb2 2. Rxf8+
{ Even though the Queens are off, White's remaining forces coordinate beautifully to invade the back rank and set up a mating combination. }
2... Kxf8 3. Nxh7+ Kg8 4. Re8+ Kxh7 5. Rh8#
{ Another example of how development matters, even without the Queens on board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 16: Martin Bier - NN, Hamburg 1878"]
[Result "*"]

{ Martin Bier - NN, Hamburg 1878  Martin Bier with another attacking masterclass. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ The Evans Gambit was a favourite of the 19th-century masters, and this game shows why. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O Nf6 7. d4
{ White has control of the center and fast development for the pawn. Black needs to focus on finishing development first and foremost. }
7... O-O { Castling is fine, but it gives White the center. } 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9.
dxe5 Nxe4 10. Qd5
{ Bringing the Queen out with tempo, and stopping Black from playing d5 himself.   10.Bf4  If White plays a random move, that gives Black the chance to play  d5 !  returning the pawn, securing the center and getting a great game. }
10... Bxc3 11. Nxc3 Nxc3 12. Qf3 Na4
{ Black has won his second pawn, but his only developed piece is far from the action. }
13. Qg3 { White lines up against the Black King, threatening Bh6. } 13... Kh8
{ 13...d6  If Black plays a nothing move, then  14.Bh6  wins at least the exchange. }
14. Bg5 { Developing with tempo ! } 14... Qe8 15. Rfe1
{ The Rook and Queen line up on the same file, always uncomfortable for the Queen. }
15... Nb6
{ Black tries to gain time by attacking the Bishop and bringing his Knight closer to the defence, but White should not automatically think about retreating. When you have such a big lead in development, your first thought should be how to attack, if possible. }
16. Bf6
{ A beautiful idea ! Black's King is defenceless against White's superior activity. }
16... Rg8
{ Black defends against mate on  g7  .   16...gxf6  17.exf6  Threatens both the Queen and the mate on  g7  (. Moving the Rook to the e-file earlier set this tactic up.) }
17. Bd3 { Now White targets  h7  . } 17... gxf6
{ It looks like White can't recapture because his Queen hangs. Did White blunder ? }
18. exf6 Rxg3 19. Rxe8+ Rg8 20. Rae1
{ Black's back rank is too weak, and White delivers mate with a Rook. Yet another example of Black grabbing material early but never finding time to develop his Queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 16.1: Martin Bier - NN, Hamburg 1878"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1qr1k/pppp1ppp/1n6/4P1B1/2B5/6Q1/P4PPP/R3R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The brilliant finish to Bier-NN, Hamburg 1878. } 1. Bf6
{ White threatens mate on  g7  ! } 1... gxf6
{ In the game, Black tried to defend with Rg8.  What happens if he takes the Bishop? }
2. exf6 { Threatening both mate on  g7  and opening an attack on the Queen. }
2... Rg8 3. Rxe8 { Pinning the Rook, and now mate is unstoppable. } 3... Rxe8
{ Had Black played  3...d5  or anything else,  4.Qg7#  is still mate, as the defending Rook is pinned! }
4. Qg7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 16.2: Martin Bier - NN, Hamburg 1878"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1q1rk/pppp1p1p/1n3p2/4P3/8/3B2Q1/P4PPP/R3R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is running out of pieces and his Queen is attacked.  How should he continue? }
1. exf6
{ 1.Qh4  looks winning, but Black has the finesse  1...f5!  2.Bxf5  Rg7  and the Rook defends against mate.  If you saw that  h7  was weak, excellent, but the real secret to this position is Black's weak back rank. }
1... Rxg3 2. Rxe8+ Rg8 3. Rae1
{ Developing the last piece, and it turns out Black's back rank is too weak!    3.Rxg8  Kxg8  4.Re1  is a tempo too slow, and Black defends with  4...Kf8. }
3... d6 4. Rxg8+ Kxg8 5. Re8#
{ This is a fantastic combination, as White's pieces are placed perfectly  (and Black's pieces absolutely anti-perfectly)  to deliver an unstoppable backrank mate.  From Martin Bier - NN, Hamburg 1878. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 17: Netzer - Mundet Riera, 2006"]
[Result "*"]

{ Netzer - Mundet Riera, 2006  White focuses on developing and playing in the center; Black focuses on pawn moves and not castling.  Goes about as well as you'd expect. }
1. e4 d6
{ Black plays a double-edged strategy of advancing in the center after a few preparatory moves first. }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { Black claims his share of the center. } 4. Nf3 Nbd7
{ Black plays solidly, but he has little space currently. } 5. g4
{ That's why White tries an interesting gambit. } 5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6
{ Black has lost time moving his Knight around, and in exchange White has pressure on the  g7  -pawn. It's not easy for Black to develop his Bishop without losing the pawn. }
7. Bc4 h6
{ An unnecessary pawn move while behind in development is always risky. } 8.
Be3 c6 { More pawn moves, more not developing. } 9. dxe5
{ A lead in development is more powerful in an open position, so White starts trading pawns. }
9... dxe5 10. Qd3 Qe7 11. O-O-O
{ It's only 11 moves in and White has completed development. It's not clear how Black will get his pieces into the game. }
11... g6
{ Prepares to develop the Bishop to  g7  , but it's ANOTHER pawn move. } 12.
Nh4
{ White plans to push f4, opening move lines, and maybe threatens a future sacrifice on  g6  to open the position. }
12... Rg8 { Black reinforces  g6  , but the Rook is very passive here. } 13. f4
b6
{ Black is trying to develop, but this is her SEVENTH pawn move in the opening. }
14. Nf3
{ The Knight returns to the center, where all of White's pieces are aiming. }
14... h5 { That's eight. } 15. fxe5
{ And this is White completely opening the center. } 15... Ng4 16. Bg5
{ White's pieces swarm around Black's weaknesses. } 16... Ndxe5
{ White's central strategy now culminates into a winning combination. } 17.
Qd8+ Qxd8 18. Rxd8#
{ Some modern players really like playing with pawns in the opening. They think the pawns can form a fortress and keep the enemy's pieces away. This game shows the antidote: push pawns, exchange pawns, and use your superior development on those open lines. }
*

