[Black "Game 18: Michiels - Van der Burght, Belgium 2002"]
[Result "*"]

{ Michiels - Van der Burght, Belgium 2002  I included this game almost entirely for the last move, which is one of my favourite tactical motifs ever. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Simple development. } 4. Bb5 a6
{ This simply ignores White's threat. } 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ White won a pawn, but Black was relying on a counter-tactic. } 6... Nxe4 7.
Nxe4 Qd4 { Black hit both Knights, so he wins his material back. } 8. O-O Qxe5
9. Re1
{ That said, his King and Queen are both on the open e-file, so he needs to be extremely careful. }
9... Be6 10. d4 { Pushing the pawn comes with tempo. } 10... Qd5 11. Bg5
{ Preventing Black from castling Queenside. } 11... Bd6 12. Bf6
{ A fascinating idea ! White tries to take advantage of Black's exposed King and Queen. }
12... O-O
{ The Bishop is immune because   12...gxf6  13.Nxf6+  forks the royal couple. }
13. Qd2 { All of White's pieces are aiming at the Kingside. } 13... Rfe8 14.
Nxd6
{ White eliminates Black's main dark-square defender. We'll see why that is important in a moment. }
14... cxd6
{ A natural move, fixing Black's structure, but it loses to a beautiful move.   14...Qxd6  was necessary. }
15. Re5
{ 15.Re5 !!  dxe5  16.Qg5  Now the pawn is in the way, and mate is unstoppable on the dark squares. This is why trading the dark-square Bishop was so vital.  g6  17.Qh6  with mate on  g7  (next.) }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 18.1: Michiels - Van der Burght, Belgium 2002"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/1ppp1ppp/p1n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Michiels-Van der Burght, Belgium 2002 reached a standard position.  How should White continue? }
1. Bxc6
{ White has pressure on the  e5   -pawn, so he should remove the defender.  1.Ba5  would let Black off the hook and give him a chance to defend better. }
1... dxc6 2. Nxe5
{ White's up a pawn, though Black can win it back at the cost of a positional concession. }
2... Nxe4 3. Nxe4 Qd4 4. O-O Qxe5 5. Re1
{ Seizing the open e-file.  Material is equal, but White has the better structure, more development and tactical ideas down the e-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 18.2: Michiels - Van der Burght, Belgium 2002"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/1p3ppp/p1ppbB2/3q4/3P4/8/PPPQ1PPP/R3R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How did Michiels-Van der Burght, Belgium 2002 end? } 1. Re5
{ A ridiculously beautiful move!  The Rook interferes with the Queen's control of  g5  .   White can't play  1.Qg5  immediately because Black will just take  1...Qxg5. }
1... dxe5 2. Qg5
{ The pawn is now in the way, and Black cannot defend a simple mating attack on the dark squares. }
2... g6 3. Qh6 exd4 4. Qg7#
{ 1. Re5!! is my favourite type of tactic, interference.  I hope you enjoyed it as much as I did! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
