[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 19: Silva - Alves, Portugal 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ Silva - Alves, Portugal 2017  White is rated 2317; Black 1331. I've included it because it shows a  some typical tactics, and b  how higher rated players outplay weaker opposition. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4
{ This is the Scotch Gambit, a strong weapon I highly recommend. It's easy for Black to go wrong, and even if he doesn't, White gets easy development and good attacking chances. }
4... Bb4+ 5. c3 dxc3 6. Nxc3
{ White has three pieces developed, lots of open lines and good central control. Black needs to be careful. }
6... Nf6
{ This just invites White to push forward.   6...d6  Stopping White's next move was best. }
7. e5 Ne4
{ 7...Ng4  If the Knight goes here, a familiar combination is possible.  8.Bxf7+ !  Kxf7  9.Ng5+  Ke8  10.Qxg4  White has regained his pawn, but more importantly Black can't castle and faces a tough defence. }
8. Qd5 { White double-attacks the Knight and  f7  , winning a piece. } 8...
Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Qxe4 Nxe5
{ Black tries to use the open e-file to counter-attack, but it doesn't work. }
11. Nxe5 d6 12. Nxf7
{ White has a lead in development, so instead of retreating he looks for tactics.   12.Nf3 ?  Re8  13.Qxe8+  Qxe8+  This was Black's idea. }
12... Rxf7 13. O-O
{ The Rook is pinned, so White is in no rush to take it. White calmly finishes development and gets all of his pieces into play, giving Black no counterplay. }
13... Qf8 14. Re1 Bd7 15. Qxb7
{ This wins a pawn but also stops Black's idea.  If White plays a normal move like   15.Bg5  then it gives Black a chance to play  Bc6  and his Bishop is active. }
15... Re8 16. Bg5 Kh8
{ Only now that Black steps out of the pin does White capture on  f7  . Notice how White waited and improved his position before capturing, gaining a lot of time in the process. }
17. Bxf7 Qxf7 18. Qxc7 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Qf5
{ And now the game ends with a simple back rank mate. } 20. Qd8+ Qf8 21. Qxf8#
{ I included this game not because it's an all-time classic, but it shows how a strong player outplays a weaker one. Black ignored the center  (common among beginners)  , which allowed a common tactic. White then finished development before doing anything else, and when he did, Black had no counterplay at all. This is a fantastic recipe for success. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 19.1: Silva - Alves, Portugal 2017"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/1bB1P3/2p2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How should White continue development, as in Silva - Alves, Portugal 2017? }
1. Nxc3
{ Taking the pawn with the Knight continues with development, though bxc3 does force the Bishop to move again and thus gains time. }
1... Nf6 2. e5
{ Black has no control over the center, so push and punish him! } 2... Ne4 3.
Qd5
{ 3.Bxf7+  is also an idea, but winning a piece is better than winning a pawn. Kudos if you saw the idea, though. }
3... Bxc3+ 4. bxc3 O-O 5. Qxe4
{ White not only finished development, he won a piece!  Not bad at all. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 20: Tabor - Rajna, Budapest 1971"]
[Result "*"]

{ Tabor - Rajna, Budapest 1971  Black weakens his King's Diagonal in an open position, and White is perfectly placed to take advantage. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 f5
{ Black tries a counter-attack, but it ignores development and weakens the King's Diagonal, a potent combination ... for White. }
4. d4 { Time is everything ! White ignores the pawn and seizes the center. }
4... fxe4 5. Nxe5 Nf6 6. Bc4 { White develops quickly, and now  f7  is weak. }
6... d5
{ Black was relying on this move, but White senses tactics and takes advantage. }
7. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ The Knight is lured away from the Kingside, exposing the King's Diagonal. }
8. Qh5+ g6 9. Nxg6
{ White is threatening to move the Knight with discovered check. } 9... Nf6
{ Black counter-attacks the Queen. There's only one move that wins for White.  If the Knight is taken   9...hxg6  then  10.Qxg6+ !  is even stronger than taking the Rook.  Ke7   10...Kd7  11.Bxd5  wins a piece with a decisive attack.  11.Bg5+  wins the Queen. }
10. Bf7+ { Sacrificing the Bishop sets up a double-check. } 10... Kxf7 11. Ne5+
{ Both White pieces are attacked, but because of the double-check, neither can be taken. }
11... Ke6 12. Qf7+ Kd6 13. Nc4#
{ Black weakened his King's Diagonal, so White was more than happy to take advantage. We can see White was focused on this weakness from the beginning, and all his moves followed from there. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 20.1: Tabor - Rajna, Budapest 1971"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pppp2pp/2n5/4pp2/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black is trying to attack before finishing development.  What is the best response? }
1. d4
{ 1.exf5  is also strong, but given the choice between winning a pawn or improving our position, taking control of the center and gaining a lead in time, we should pick the second option every time. }
1... fxe4 2. Nxe5 { 2.Nxe4  is also strong. } 2... Nf6 3. Bc4
{ This is the ideal move we want to play: develops the Bishop and aims at the weakness near the King.  We need to have a good answer to d5, though. }
3... d5 4. Nxd5
{ Much stronger than  4.Bb5  , as White prepares to attack on the weakened King's Diagonal. }
4... Nxd5 5. Qh5+
{ White had a winning attack in Tabor - Rajna, Budapest 1971. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 20.2: Tabor - Rajna, Budapest 1971"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp4p/2n3p1/3nN2Q/2BPp3/8/PPP2PPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The King's Diagonal is obviously weak in Tabor - Rajna, Budapest 1971.  How did White finish this one off? }
1. Nxg6
{ Standard and thematic. If  1...hxg6  2.Qxg6+  Kd7  3.Qf5+  White picks up a piece on  d5  (and continues the assault against the Black King.) }
1... Nf6 { Black attacks the Queen, preventing any discovered checks. } 2. Bf7+
{ White hits  f7  and prepares a discovered double-check.  This is similar to Horvath - Mayer, Budapest 1914.  Do you see how these common ideas start repeating themselves over and over?  And how learning them can't help but improve your game? }
2... Kxf7 3. Ne5+
{ The King is dragged into the open, where the White pieces coordinate perfectly against him. }
3... Ke6 4. Qf7+ Kd6 5. Nc4#
{ A lovely finish that shows the dangers of the King's Diagonal and the power of coordinated pieces against an exposed King. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 21: Kronsforth - Bothmann, Dortmund 1988"]
[Result "*"]

{ Kronsforth - Bothmann, Dortmund 1988  In this game Black gets too fixated on exploiting a positional advantage on the Kingside, to the point he fatally neglects his development. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The King's Gambit, everyone's favourite. } 2... exf4 3. Nf3 d5
{ Black correctly returns the pawn to advance in the center. This is the easiest way to play, in my opinion, and I like easy. }
4. e5
{ A weak non-developing pawn move; the pawn mostly gets in the way of White's pieces. }
4... g5
{ The opening is about development, yes, but Black is threatening to play g4, as the e-pawn takes away the  e5  -square from the Knight. White will end up losing time, and your opponent losing time is pretty much the same thing as you gaining time. Of course, simple development was also excellent. }
5. h3 Nh6 6. d4 Nf5
{ Yes, the Knight moves twice, but it threatens to go to  g3  , where it will a  be amazing, and b  force White to lose time. But yes, simple development would also be excellent. }
7. Bd3 Ng3 8. Rg1 Be6
{ Not a bad move, but not the most useful one either; the Bishop isn't much more active here than on its original square. Nc6 or Be7 are natural moves that improve the position. }
9. Nbd2 h5
{ Black sees his great Knight on  g3  and tries to increase his positional advantage on that side of the board, but the opening isn't about gaining positional advantages, it's about developing as fast as possible. }
10. Nf1 { Trying to trade the annoying Knight. } 10... g4
{ Black sticks to his flawed strategy. } 11. Nxg3 gxf3 12. Bxf4 fxg2
{ Five moves ago, Black had a great position; now he has one piece developed to White's four. Something has gone wrong.  Oh, right, it was all those non-developing pawn moves. }
13. Rxg2 Qh4
{ And now he brings his Queen out ! Still focusing on the Kingside, ignoring his development. }
14. Qd2 Bxh3
{ Moving the Bishop again, his Queen is out, his King is in the center, White is near fully developed ... yes, this position demands a tactical refutation. White finds it. }
15. Bg5 { The Queen is nearly trapped ! } 15... Bh6
{ Black finds a tricky defence, pinning the Bishop, but White can finesse a material gain: }
16. Bxh4 Bxd2+ 17. Rxd2
{ White has emerged up a piece, so Black resigned. Notice that, even though White had some weaknesses near his King, the tactics favoured White. Why ? Because tactics flow from a superior position, and White had near full development to Black's two pieces. Of course the tactics worked. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 21.1: Kronsforth - Bothmann, Dortmund 1988"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kb1r/ppp2p2/8/3pP2p/3P1B1q/3B2Nb/PPPQ2R1/R3K3 w Qkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black is way behind in development, his King is in the center and his Queen is out early.  Our Rook is also under attack.  What do we do? }
1. Bg5 { The Queen is near trapped! } 1... Bh6
{ Black offers a crafty counter-pin, threatening to take our Queen with check.   Instead  1...Qg4  , the only available square, would allow  2.Bf5  Qf3  3.Bxh3  and White wins a piece. }
2. Bxh4 Bxd2+ 3. Rxd2
{ The Rook recaptures, saving it, and White emerges a solid piece up in Kronsforth - Bothmann, Dortmund 1988. }
