[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 22: Paul Morphy - Alonzo Morphy, New Orleans 1849"]
[Result "*"]

{ Paul Morphy - Alonzo Morphy, New Orleans 1849  My friend 'PixelatedParcel' said I needed to include this game, but I had to credit him for finding it. This one's for you, Pix. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ Paul Morphy plays the Evans Gambit, a very fun and very violent attempt to secure the initiative. }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 { By luring the Bishop to  b4  , now c3 comes with tempo. }
5... Bc5
{ This move makes little sense, as d4 is coming and the Bishop needs to move again. Be7 or Ba5 are critical. }
6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb6
{ The Bishop has now moved four times in the first seven moves, so White has a significant lead in time: easy development, dominant pawn center, ready to castle. }
8. O-O Na5 { Black now moves his Knight a second time ! } 9. Bd3 d5
{ This is a critical mistake: do NOT open the center when you are a  behind in development, and b  with your King on the open e-file ! True, Black wants to fight for the center, but not like this, not after wasting so much time earlier. }
10. exd5 { The e-file is open and ready for use. } 10... Qxd5
{ And also, the Queen is there to be harassed with tempo as well. } 11. Ba3
{ The Bishop goes to a beautiful diagonal, and now Black cannot castle Kingside. }
11... Be6
{ Black thus prepares to castle Queenside, but with White's open b- and c-files, that likely won't be any safer. }
12. Nc3 Qd7 13. d5
{ With near perfect development, Morphy now capitalized, blasting open the center. If the Bishop moves, then the open e-file will be decisive. }
13... Bxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Re1+
{ Here's a sample of how the game may have ended.   15.Re1+  Kd8  16.Bc4  Qxd1  17.Raxd1+  Kc8  18.Re8# }
*

