[SetUp "1"]

{ Having just gambited the b-pawn, as in Paul Morphy - Alonzo Morphy, New Orleans 1849, how should White finish development? }
1. c3
{ This is the point, hitting the Bishop with tempo and preparing to dominate the center. }
1... Bc5 { This allows the Bishop to get hit with tempo again. } 2. d4 exd4 3.
cxd4 Bb6 4. O-O
{ White has a beautiful position, control of the center and easy development, which is well worth the pawn investment. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 22.2: Paul Morphy - Alonzo Morphy, New Orleans 1849"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k1nr/ppp2ppp/1b2b3/n2q4/3P4/B2B1N2/P4PPP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nc3 { Developing with tempo, as natural as it gets. } 1... Qd7 2. d5
{ Opening up e-file! This is better than  2.Re1  immediately, because Black can  2...O-O-O  away from the pressure, though his King remains far from safe. }
2... Bxd5 3. Nxd5 Qxd5 4. Re1+
{ Black was getting eviscerated in Paul Morphy - Alonzo Morphy, New Orleans 1849, and he resigned.  The open center is too much. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 23: NN - Kahn, Nice 1941"]
[Result "*"]

{ NN - Kahn, Nice 1941  White pushes Black towards his Kingside, which ends badly. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Simple development so far. } 4. d4
{ White immediately opens the center. Controlling the center is a key principle, so it's a good strategy. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Black counters by attacking White's  e4  -pawn, forcing a concession. } 6.
Nxc6
{ White needs to exchange the Knight before playing Bd3.   6.Bd3 ??  Nxd4   6.f3 ?!  This weakens the King's Diagonal.  O-O  7.Bc4  d5 !  And Black is threatening to open the e-file before White has castled. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
{ Both sides have castled, so the opening is nearly complete. Just one piece each needs to be developed. }
8... d5 { Black fights for the center, and now his Bishop is free to develop. }
9. e5
{ White tries to secure an advanced central pawn, but this pushes Black towards the White King.   9.exd5  cxd5  This is the usual way of playing, where White argues that Black's central pawn is a target, with Qf3 and Bg5 coming next. }
9... Ng4 10. f4
{ White defends his central pawn, but his King is now wide open. } 10... Qh4
{ Black immediately jumps in on the weakness, and White is defenceless. } 11.
h3 { 11.g3  Qxh2# } 11... Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Qg3
{ The Queen slinks in, threatening mate on  h2  . } 13. hxg4
{ Taking the Knight stops mate on  h2  , but... } 13... Qh4#
{ ... now mate comes on  h4  . White made only one real mistake, but that mistake was weakening his King, and that's all it takes. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 23.1: NN - Kahn, Nice 1941"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p1p2ppp/2p2n2/3pP3/1b6/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Obviously our Knight is attacked, but what is the best way to react? } 1...
Ng4 2. f4
{ Black's Knight maneuver tempted this common blunder from White.  Now the King is too exposed. }
2... Qh4
{ GM Yasser Seirawan has said that if Black can ever threaten a mate in 1, something had gone wrong for White. Black threatens mate on  h2  . }
3. h3 Bc5+ 4. Kh1 Qg3
{ Again threatening mate on  h2  !    4...Nf2+  wins material, but why settle for an exchange when you can get the whole prize? }
5. hxg4 Qh4#
{ It only takes a few inaccuracies near your King to go from fine to completely losing.  That's what happened to White here.  From NN - Kahn, Nice 1941 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 24: geeb - Young Smithy, Internet 2005"]
[Result "*"]

{ 'geeb' - Young Smithy, Internet 2005  I include this game as a warning of sorts: chess is a concrete game, and every rule has exceptions. Even the rules I've spent the last 100 examples harping on. }
1. d4 g6 2. c4 f5
{ In this game, I disobey virtually every opening rule I teach in this course ... and I win in dominating fashion. In the first two moves, I'm moving pawns instead of pieces and weakening my King's Diagonal. }
3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bf4 d6 { That's three pawn moves in the first four moves. } 5.
Nf3 Bg7 6. Nd2 Nh5 { Moving a piece twice in the opening. } 7. e3 Nxf4 8. exf4
Bxd4 { Getting greedy, winning material instead of finishing development. } 9.
Qf3 c6 { Unnecessary pawn moves that don't help development. } 10. Nb3 Bg7 11.
O-O-O O-O { At least I get castling right ! } 12. Bd3
{ What's funny is that White is near fully developed and Black is near fully undeveloped ... and I spent the next five moves still not developing ... and I get a winning position. }
12... a5 13. Rhe1 a4 14. Nd2 a3 15. Ndb1 axb2+
{ The a-pawn marched down the board and tore White's position apart. } 16. Kd2
e5 17. g3 e4 { He then falls for a simple fork. } 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Rxe4 Bf5
{ I finally develop a piece, so my opponent naturally resigns :D  In all seriousness, I show this game to highlight the following: chess is a concrete game, and every rule has exceptions. If you look at this game with a computer, you'll see that most of my moves were engine approved... even though they violate every principle. The principles will help you in the vast majority of games. Ignoring opening principles leads to far, far, far more losses than wins  (out of over 100 examples in this course, this is the only one where the person with a lead in development loses)  . Treat them as guidelines, not immutable rules.   In conclusion, though the general principles are extremely powerful, they are no substitute for calculation.  If you can calculate that violating a principle is okay, then have faith in your judgement and do it.  Just don't expect it to happen too often. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Section III - Annotated Games"]
[Black "Game 25: Reti - Tartakower, Vienna 1910"]
[Result "*"]

{ Reti - Tartakover, Vienna 1910   I've included this game as a final bonus, simply because it's beautiful. If you've never seen it before, you're welcome. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qd3
{ White develops his Queen early, which should be a no-no.   5.Nxf6+  is, of course, the right move, as no matter how Black recaptures his pawn structure is worse. }
5... e5
{ Black responds by opening the center, a risky strategy when behind in development. }
6. dxe5 Qa5+ { And especially risky when you then bring the Queen out ! } 7.
Bd2 Qxe5 8. O-O-O
{ White ignores the threat against his Knight and completes development with all speed. It looks like White is trying to use the e-file against Black's exposed King, but it's actually the neighbouring file that decides the game. }
8... Nxe4 9. Qd8+ { Oh, baby ! The type of move we all dream of playing ! }
9... Kxd8 10. Bg5+ { Black resigned, as it's mate next move. } 10... Kc7
{ 10...Ke8  11.Rd8#  and we have the Opera mate, a fitting bookend to this course, as the Opera Game was the first game we studied. }
11. Bd8#
{ One of the most brilliant and beautiful combinations in chess history, and it was all thanks to fast development.   Time is everything ! }
*

