[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's finish this course off in style! } 1. O-O-O { Time is everything! }
1... Nxe4 2. Qd8+ Kxd8 3. Bg5+ Kc7 4. Bd8# { Reti - Tartakover, Vienna 1910 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Conclusion"]
[Black "Bonus Annotated Game!"]
[Result "*"]

{ Alexsur81  (2591)  - Winquitter  (2369)  , 3min Blitz, Lichess.org   This is a bonus game I witnessed after creating the core of this course. Notice how a very strong modern blitz player can still make common mistakes. Also, White's rating has been as high 2800 at blitz, and Black's 2500, so these are very strong players ... but Black's mistakes make him look like a beginner.  Link: @@LinkStart@@https://lichess.org/xlwilg3i#0@@LinkEnd@@ }
1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ White plays the King's Gambit, offering a pawn for fast development, and this seems to completely throw Black off his game. }
2... exf4 3. Bc4
{ This move develops the Bishop, of course, and tempts Black to make a check with his Queen. }
3... d6
{ 3...Qh4+  4.Kf1  White's King is misplaced, but Black's Queen is developed early, and White will win further time with Nf3 next. White's initiative can become quite strong here. }
4. Nf3 g5 { Black is moving pawns and worrying about material ! Oh no. } 5. h4
{ Breaks up Black's pawns, leaving only weaknesses behind. } 5... g4 6. Ng5
{ f7  is now threatened. } 6... Nh6
{ Because of all his previous pawn moves, Black is forced to develop his Knight to a sad square to defend  f7  . }
7. d4
{ In addition to his development, White has complete control of the center. }
7... Qe7
{ Black now moves his Queen early ! Black spent a lot of time here, and then played his next moves very quickly, so he was clearly formulating a plan. Unfortunately, he came up with the wrong one.  Returning the pawn and finishing development seems best:   7...Nc6  8.Bxf4  Bg7  and there's pressure on  d4  (and Black has caught up in development, though White's pieces are better placed and Black has many weaknesses because of his early pawn moves.) }
8. Nc3 { White develops. } 8... c6 { Black makes an unnecessary pawn move. } 9.
O-O { White castles and has most of his army in the game. } 9... f6
{ And Black responds by trying to win material, with another pawn move ! Of course, White's Knight could have been trapped by this move since move 7, but White is willing to sacrifice it to open lines and gain a lead in time. Black should NOT be thinking about winning material in the opening, especially when he is so far behind in development. Time is everything ! }
10. Bxf4 b5 { Another pawn move. } 11. Bb3 b4 { And another. } 12. Ne2 fxg5 13.
Bxg5 Qxe4
{ We can see Black's idea: he pushed his Queenside pawns so he could force White's Knight to move, and now he wins the e-pawn ... when his King is already in the center and can't castle ... and he had already won a Knight. In other words, Black had the complete wrong focus: he tried to win material instead of finishing development. Now White's developed army will make short work of him. }
14. Ng3
{ Notice how easy this is. White moves the Knight to a better square, gains tempo on the Queen and opens the e-file. }
14... Qg6 15. Rf6 { Now he improves his Rook with tempo. } 15... Qg7 16. Qd3
{ The Queen slides forward, allowing the last piece into the game. } 16... d5
{ Trying to cut the Bishop off, but there's nothing Black can do. } 17. Re1+
{ It's move 17, and White is fully developed. Black has two pieces developed, one his Queen and the other a Knight on the edge of the board doing nothing. Black is toast. }
17... Kd7 { The King tries to run. } 18. Rxh6 { White wins back his piece. }
18... Bd6 { Black finally develops a piece ! } 19. Nf5
{ But then he immediately loses it, so he resigns. I wanted to show this game for several reasons.   1. Most of my examples came from the last century, so it's nice to see people playing like Morphy in 2019;   2.  Modern players still violate opening principles, and they can get punished in the exact same way.   3. Many of you love playing blitz, and you'll get strange openings like this frequently. Here's proof that following the principles still works, and violating them can lead to quick defeat.   4. White only spent 38s on this entire game. Clearly, a big reason is because he is a very strong player, but following the opening principles, where you focus on development over anything else, allows you to play faster. You aren't thinking about winning pawns or trying to attack early. You focus on development, and once you are developed you use it. Powerful stuff.   5. It's a pretty game, and chess should be pretty! }
*

