[White "Appendix I: Smithy's Practical Tips"]
[Black "Practical Tips"]
[Result "*"]

{ These tips assume you are under 1500 Elo or so.  They work for everyone, but the goal is to give simple, concrete advice to the more beginner players.  Advanced players may find these less applicable.  @@HeaderStart@@IN GENERAL@@HeaderEnd@@  1. Play lots of gambits: if you've gone through all the annotated games, you've seen the power of the gambits.  Give up a pawn for rapid development.  When it works, you feel amazing.  It also gives you a better idea of when to sacrifice pawns or pieces later in the game.  If you never play gambits, it's hard to get a sense of when you get enough compensation for a pawn, say.  Playing gambits helps improve this sense.  1.1. Don't accept gambits: See above, but in reverse.  As White, you have a little more leeway, but being a beginner and facing a gambit as Black isn't a lot of fun.  Return the material asap.  See the video for concrete examples.  2. As Black, play 1.e4 e5, 1.d4 d5 and 1.c4 e5: This is a practical suggestion. If you do this, you greatly minimize the amount of theory you need to know, and you can operate on basic principles for a long time.  2.1. Relatedly, if White ever puts two pawns in the center, exchange one immediately without thinking: Okay, maybe think a little, but never let White have the center.  3. If you have a choice, move pieces instead of pawns.  4. Understand why you play every move that you play.  Chessable lets you learn lots of different openings, but be careful.  Don't blindly trust the books.  Even if the book is 100% right, if you don't know why it is right or what to do next, it won't help you.  It's better to follow opening principles that you do understand, even if the books and computers say it is second best, then play the best and not know what to do.  5. Simple is good. You don't need to play mainline razor sharp theory.  You'll probably get better results early on if you don't, in all honesty.  6. As a general opening goal, aim to have all minor pieces active by move 10, and strive to have your Rooks connected by move 15.  Treat it like a countdown timer: every move takes you closer to zero, and you want to be fully developed before then.  If you do this, you'd be very unlikely to lose pre-20 moves, barring chess blindness.  Again, treat the above as friendly advice.  It's what I would tell Young Smithy if I had a chance.  @@HeaderStart@@ IN SPECIFIC@@HeaderEnd@@  As White, play 1.e4 and ...  ... against 1... e5: Play something with an early d4.  Scotch Game, Scotch Gambit, Italian, Max Lange Attack, Ruy Lopez Center Game, just play d4 early.  This puts more pressure on Black and gives him more chances to go wrong.  There are various Chessable courses on most of these if you need more detailed advice.  I've listed several in the 'Reference' Chapter.  ... against the Sicilian, 1...c5: Play the Smith-Morra Gambit.  Develop normally.  ... against anything else: Exchange pawns at the first opportunity.  Develop normally.  Follow the principles.  If you want to play 1.d4, don't do it.  If you insist ...  ... play the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit.  Theoryhack has a free course on this, linked in the 'Reference' Chapter.  As Black ...  ... against the King's Gambit: play d5 and then take on  f4  .  Develop normally.  Alternatively, decline the gambit with 2... Bc5 and develop normally.  ... against other gambits: ignore the pawn and play d5 instead, if possible.  ... against anything else: play Bc5 and then Nf6.  Once White defends his  e4  -pawn, play d6.  Develop normally.  Follow the principles.  Against 1.d4, follow the 'Short and Sweet Slav' and/or 'Crush the London' on Chessable.  This isn't an in-depth repertoire, obviously.  This is just a way to start playing with the least amount of homework and memory possible. }
