{ If you've finished this course, hats off to you, and I hope you enjoyed it.  Of course, the next questions is, where do you go from here?  I should point out here that what you learned in this course is all the opening knowledge you need for a pretty long time.  I got to roughly 1600 Elo in online chess knowing only the principles and tactics shown here, and when I learned some common plans in various typical openings I got to 1800.  In other words, I got to 1800 Elo with very little theory knowledge, and even today, I rely on these principles in openings where I don't know  (or have forgotten!)  the theory.  That said, here are some suggestions for your continued chess education.  
@@HeaderStart@@Openings@@HeaderEnd@@  If you want to learn the basic plans and ideas of various openings as mentioned above, the gold standard is Fundamental Chess Openings by Paul van der Sterren.  That book, combined with the training you've done here, is all the opening knowledge you need until you're approaching the advanced level.  I also have a YouTube series that will go over all the basic opening plans, and you can find that on my blog  (@@LinkStart@@www.SmithyQ.com@@LinkEnd@@)  or directly on YouTube:  (@@LinkStart@@http://bit.ly/SmithyOpeningSurvey@@LinkEnd@@)   That said, this is Chessable, so you're probably looking for course suggestions as well.  Here goes.  Chessable has several 'Short and Sweet' courses that cover the basic ideas behind many popular openings.  These are the perfect introduction to these openings, as they are explained with excellent verbal annotations and the absolute minimum amount of moves to memorize.  They are also free, so you really can't beat these.  If you want specific gambit recommendations, here are some excellent places to start:  Theoryhack's Beginner Blitz Repertoire: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/a-beginners-blitz-repertoire/course/7832/@@LinkEnd@@  Ralv's Greco Gambit: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/great-gambits-the-greco/course/20940/@@LinkEnd@@  NM Han Schut's Scotch Gambit: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/scotch-gambit-modern-attack-beginners-guide-/course/13869/@@LinkEnd@@ and Evans Gambit: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/evans-gambit-beginners-guide/course/13833/@@LinkEnd@@  These are either free or very inexpensive, and they lead to open games where you will get ample opportunities to try out the tactics you learned in this course.  For the more advanced students who studied this course for some reason, FM Kaldas90's 1.d4 repertoire is a fun one with excellent author support: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/go-for-the-throat-play-1d4/course/23159/@@LinkEnd@@  @@HeaderStart@@Study the Great Masters@@HeaderEnd@@  The best way to study chess as a whole is to review the games of the great masters, and the best way to start is with the giants of the past: Morphy, Tarrasch, Lasker, Capablanca, Alekhine are some of the best.  I've mentioned that Tarrasch was my favourite player, and studying his games transformed my chess.  In terms of specific recommendations.  Reti's 'Master's of the Chessboard'  (highly recommended)   Chernev's 'Logical Chess Move by Move'  Alekhine's 'My Best Games of Chess'  Seirawan's 'Winning Chess Brilliancies'  (and really, the entire Winning Chess Series is an excellent introduction to every phase of the game)   For the more advanced or ambitious out there:  Fischer's 'My 60 Memorable Games'  Bronstein's 'Zurich International Chess Tournament 1953' and 'The Sorcerer's Apprentice'  Tarrasch's '300 Chess Games'  (though it's much easier to find this if you read German...)   Kasparov's series 'My Great Predecessors' ... or really anything by Kasparov   If you are ever unsure what to study, review annotated master games.  I cannot recommend this enough.  Chessable is starting to get game collections on its platform, but this type of material is likely best used in book form.  @@HeaderStart@@Tactics@@HeaderEnd@@  If you enjoyed the tactical section of this course, then learning more about tactics is an excellent choice.  There are many, many, many resources available, but I'll point out the following:  On Chessable, AlanB's 'On the Attack' series is free and excellent.  Study them.  Just do it.  He also has some premium products that are highly rated and worth checking out, especially if you enjoy his teaching style.  If you want a systematic tactics course that teaches from the ground up, try Benedictine's Tactics course:  (@@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/common-chess-patterns/course/13348/@@LinkEnd@@)  It slowly builds up from simple to more complex patterns, similar to my tactical section but better, and not restricted only to opening tactics.  Well worth the small cost.  Finally, to test your tactics, the best website by far it ChessTempo: @@LinkStart@@www.ChessTempo.com@@LinkEnd@@.  It's free, it's quality, and no other similar site comes close.  I will say this: if you want to LEARN tactics, a book or Chessable course is probably best; if you want to see how WELL you can see tactics, or if you want to TEST your tactics, that's where sites like ChessTempo come in.  @@HeaderStart@@Endgames@@HeaderEnd@@  Theoryhack to the rescue again: he has a free basic endgame course, and this should be your first stop: @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/basic-endgames/course/6371/@@LinkEnd@@  When you're done studying that, go review Capablanca's games.  Find a book or just find a database of his games and go through them.  Even without commentary, if you review 50 Capablanca endgames, you'll be a better endgame player than most.  I often outplay my opponents in endgames, and I attribute this to studying Capablanca.  @@HeaderStart@@Other Resources@@HeaderEnd@@  Chess.com is the bigger site, but Lichess.org does everything better: less lag, free features, no ads, cleaner visuals, detailed stats, no restrictions on game analysis, etc etc.  I play there pretty much exclusively nowadays, and I highly recommend it.  There are numerous chess YouTube Channels out there, and hearing a strong player explain his or her thoughts in real time can be invaluable.  There are too many to list, so I'll limit myself to two.  First, perhaps the best channel, the St Louis Chess Club:  (@@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCM-ONC2bCHytG2mYtKDmIeA@@LinkEnd@@)  In particular, watch anything by GM Yasser Seirawan, who is known as the Bob Ross of chess.  His stories are just as entertaining as they are educational.  Second, a small channel that deserves far more exposure, GM Mykhaylo Oleksiyenko's channel:  (@@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCC2sn2vrw2KdSafmw_ZPh2A@@LinkEnd@@)  This may be more suited to the more advanced players out there, but GM Oleksiyenko is a masterful teacher at explaining the logic behind positional concepts, though it does require having a firm grasp of the basics.  @@HeaderStart@@More Smithy@@HeaderEnd@@  If you like my teaching style, you may find my blog interesting: @@LinkStart@@www.SmithyQ.com@@LinkEnd@@  It's not super active at the moment, but I've written about many different topics and interests over the years.  I do in-depth analysis of my games, as well as writing about my chess journey and various thoughts on chess and life in general.  Also, the best spot to ever ask me questions or get a hold of me.  If you liked my videos, I have a YouTube channel:  (@@LinkStart@@https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCw8GHKVm0dnaSeG96Ohwjcw@@LinkEnd@@)  I updated semi-regularly, so take a look if you enjoy 20+min analysis of games, where I mostly focus on the ideas behind the moves.  If anyone has anything to add, especially if it's a free resource, please add a comment so others can see as well.  @@HeaderStart@@Reader Suggestions@@HeaderEnd@@The Complete Idiot's Guide to Chess Openings, by William Aramil  (content appears similar to this course; could be useful to get a deeper understanding or a different perspective on the opening principles)   A Guide to Chess Improvement: The Best of Novice Nook, by Dan Heisman  (Kindle version is available but sloppily converted from the paperback; grab it used if you can)   Back to Basics: Tactics, by NM Dan Heisman  (considered a classic introduction to tactics; now available on Chessable! @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/back-to-basics-tactics/course/23488/@@LinkEnd@@) }
