{ All game analysis was done by me, with computer assistance.  Opening principles have been repeated by strong players to those just starting out for years and years.  I first came across them in Tarrasch’s, “The Game of Chess,” which has an in-depth discussion of tempi as well.  GM Igor Smirnov’s chess course “Opening Laboratory 2” furthered the idea of “time is everything.”  An excellent resource.  The first opening book I ever read was Reinfeld and Horowitz’s “Winning Chess Openings.”  Though seriously outdated, it describes the ideas and plans behind 10 of the most common openings, and it was the foundation of my opening knowledge when I first started out.  Though not directly reference in this course, the way I view theory is heavily influenced by this book, and it deserves credit for that.  In terms of finding examples, many were common traps or everyday examples that I picked up over the years.  The decision to use these particular examples in the tactics section  (ie, weakness of)  f7  (, open e-file, etc)  was based entirely on my personal experience.  Any errors or omissions are my own.  The following resources helped in finding example games:  Chernev’s “1000 Best Short Games of Chess”, highly recommended.  Polgar’s “5334 Chess Problems,” specifically the section on 600 Miniature Games that were organized by theme.  ChessTempo  (@@LinkStart@@www.chesstempo.com@@LinkEnd@@)  was used to find more modern examples by theme.  Dodgy's 'Sicilian Tactics - 1000 Puzzles!' here on Chessable was used during beta testing to get more examples.  I have read countless chess books over the years, and many of them have helped shape my outlook and perspective on this great game.  If I made a comment or used an example that looked like an example from somewhere else, this was likely because I did read it before and absorbed it via osmosis, not recalling the source.  No plagiarism was intended.  If you find any such instance in my work, please let me know and I will assign the appropriate citation.   That said, the vast bulk of this course came from the sources listed above. }
